<seg id="1">Report on the results of parallel checks on the administration of value added tax between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted material informs about the progress and results of the parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Czech Republic Control Authority, which focused on the administration of Value Added Tax Exchange System (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so revenues from value added tax affect not only the national budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">Parallel control actions were aimed in particular at checking the progress of tax administrations in examining the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of VIES enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of value added tax payers in individual Member States of the European Union and on commercial transactions carried out by such payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">Mismatch between data in the VIES system and data in the VAT return filed by the payer should alert the tax administrator to suspicious cases and allow detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefit of the parallel checks was not only the exchange of information on the procedure of the financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but in particular the examination of the use of the VIES system in checking the application of the right to value added tax in intracommunity transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained in the implementation of parallel controls is beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of further parallel checks in cooperation with the audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of parallel checks on the administration of value added tax for the period from 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of control: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration, (SK) Control of tax authorities' procedures for the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and the performance of VIES tasks for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic ("SAO, Czech Republic") and the Czech Audit Office of the Republic ("SAO SR") concluded on 12.9.2005 the Surveillance Cooperation Agreement.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in the implementation of the parallel control actions "Value Added Tax Administration," included in the SAO Control Plan for 2005 under No. 05/19 and "Control of the Tax Procedure control and enforcement of VAT on value added and tasks under the VIES system on exchange of funds by Member States, " included in the SAO's audit plan under No 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel control actions were coordinated.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated control was developed within the meaning of European Enforcement Regulation No 31 for INTOSAI control standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information to the extent specified by the Treaty and drawing up a joint final report on the outcome of the parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated inspection was to verify selected cases of delivery and acquisition of goods in suspicious commercial transactions between the taxpayers of value added tax from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic") and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Slovak Republic").</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties contractually undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the Value Added Tax Information Exchange System (VIES) and data on requests received and sent to verify commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the Czech Republic, the control was carried out by the state budget department and the territorial unions of central Bohemia, northwestern Bohemia, southern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the Ministry of Finance and 12 Financial Offices: The Financial Office in Mladá Split, Tax Office in Cologne, Tax Office in Teplice, Tax Office in Karlovy Vary, Tax Office in Tábor, Financial Office Brno III, Tax Office in Znojmo, Tax Office in Zlín, Tax Office in Šumperk, Tax Office in Ostrava I, Tax Office for Prague 7 and Tax Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The control on the territory of the SR was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with Exposures of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: Tax department Bratislava I, Tax department Komárno, Tax department Trenčín, Tax department Prievidza, Tax department Prievidza</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of checks:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel control actions was to examine the procedure of the financial and tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") after the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the Single Internal Market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as "the EU") and to examine the use of the electronic information system VIES, in particular when checking the application of the VAT exemption claim.</seg>
<seg id="27">The controlled period of coordinated control was the period from 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions In EU Member States, an electronic VIES system is introduced to enable tax administrations to check whether the supplier has been entitled to exempt taxable transactions from VAT and to verify in the country of destination whether the purchaser has properly declared and taxed the goods acquired.</seg>
<seg id="29">VIES is not centralised within the EU, each Member State develops its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The examination identified differences of national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and SR in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The aggregated reports shall indicate the delivery values of the goods to other EU Member States, the values of the services provided shall not be included in the summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="32">Data from summary reports filed by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of the tax authorities, where they compare with data on deliveries of goods to other EU Member States listed in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities transmit data from summary reports to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In SR, data from summary reports filed by Slovak payers at tax offices are only transferred to electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of SR (Customs).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of supplies of goods and the value of services to other EU Member States on separate lines of VAT returns, which allows to compare the values listed in the aggregated reports with the value of supplies of goods according to the VAT return and to identify any differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the SR, the values of the goods and services supplied to other EU Member States are aggregated on the common line of the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="37">Consequently, in SR, the system does not allow to automatically identify differences between the values of delivery of goods according to tax returns and summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the value of supplies of goods in VAT tax returns enables the data comparison results to be used to check the VAT exemption for supplies to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="39">The received data from the summary reports filed by payers in other EU Member States are processed into Customs and compared with the value of the acquisition of goods indicated by the payers from the Czech Republic or SR in the VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the SR, these data are sent to the tax authorities and the tax authorities themselves decide which cases of differences will be examined.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) determines which quantified differences between the values of delivery and acquisition of goods must be examined by the tax administrators and transmits the list of these cases to the local tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that, for the most significant derogations, it will be checked whether the VAT was declared at the correct level when the goods were acquired.</seg>
<seg id="43">The audit also highlighted some problems in the VAT management system due to the different reporting of intracommunity transactions (i.e. delivery and acquisition of goods by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Summary reports are made in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum time limit for processing and dispatching data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">Reducing the period for which summary reports are submitted to one month, together with reducing the time limit for processing, would allow earlier access to VIES data.</seg>
<seg id="46">The tax authorities could thus more effectively verify whether VAT was declared at the correct level in intracommunity transactions.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, the submission of VAT returns and summary declarations for the same tax period (month) would allow for a faster verification of whether the payer has reported in both the aggregated report and the VAT return the same value of the delivery of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="48">Differences between the delivery values reported by EU payers and the acquisition values reported by payers from the Czech Republic and SR were due, among other things, to different reporting of intracommunity and acquisition data in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These included, for example, the presentation of advances received in summary reports or the reporting of intracommunity deliveries in the supplier's summary report in a different quarter than intracommunity acquisitions in the purchaser's VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="50">A harmonisation of the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would make the control activities of the national tax administrations more effective.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was also aimed at examining selected intracommunity transactions between the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, 40 cases of commercial transactions between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined, where there were doubts about their implementation or suspected tax evasion on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR have identified among others the following:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax entities have declared in their VAT returns, for the purpose of unduly obtaining excessive VAT deduction, intracommunity transactions which have not actually taken place;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax entities reported intracommunity deliveries in the context of carousel transactions that deliberately reduced the value of supplies multiple times in order to draw excessive VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers reported in their VAT returns and summary reports intracommunity supplies of exempt goods to purchasers who were so-called "lost companies" and did not grant tax on acquired goods;</seg>
<seg id="57">suppliers have made intracommunitary supplies of VAT-exempt goods to tax entities which have not been registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In such cases, the supply should not have been exempt from VAT and should have been taxed in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">suppliers reported intracommunity supplies in their VAT returns at a higher value than the intracommunity acquisition declared by the purchasers, and in some cases VAT was declared incorrectly.</seg>
<seg id="60">The knowledge gained in the control action showed that the VIES system provides tax administrations with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intracommunity transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">Tax administrations should pay particular attention to the rigorous examination of the differences between data reported by VAT payers and data in the VIES system and the use of all information in tax procedures.</seg>
<seg id="62">Issue of value added tax after Czech and Slovak accession to the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1.5.2004 the Czech Republic and SR became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">Internal borders and border controls on intra-EU movements of goods have been abolished after EU accession.</seg>
<seg id="66">The VAT administrator was by 30 April 2004 the competent financial and tax office, with the exception of imports of goods and occasional bus services in the country where the tax administrator was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new Act No. 235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter "Act No. 235/2004 Coll.") and Act No. 222/2004 Z. z., on value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 222/2004 Z. z. ") the VAT administration transferred from customs offices to financial and tax offices when purchasing goods and services (formerly imported) from other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="68">By delivering the goods in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of Section 13 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means the transfer of the right to dispose of goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">The delivery of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU Member State is the delivery of goods that have actually been shipped or transported to another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="70">According to the provisions of Section 64 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. this is an exempt taxable transaction with a right to deduct VAT when the goods are delivered to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">For the delivery of goods in SR according to the provisions of Section 8 of Act No 222/2004 Z. z. considers the supply of tangible property to change ownership.</seg>
<seg id="72">The supply of goods shall also be deemed to involve the transfer of goods owned by a taxable person from the country to another Member State where such goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on his behalf to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">According to the provisions of Section 43 of Law No 222/2004 Z. z. the supply of goods from the country to another Member State shall be exempt from VAT where the purchaser is a person identified for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">By acquiring goods from another EU Member State in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of Section 16 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of goods dispatched or transported to the purchaser by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Czech payer purchases goods at a price excluding VAT and is obliged in the Czech Republic to declare VAT according to the provisions of Section 25 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll., and in fulfilment of the conditions laid down in Section 73 of this Act he is entitled to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="76">The acquisition of goods in the Czech Republic from another EU Member State is in the Slovak Republic according to the provisions of Section 11 of Law No. 222/2004 Z. z. the acquisition of the right to dispose as an owner of movable tangible property dispatched or transported by the purchaser by the supplier or the purchaser, or for their account, to the territory of another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">The tax liability in the SR is incurred by the payer when acquiring goods from another Member State in accordance with the provisions of Section 20 of Act No. 222/2004 Z.z.</seg>
<seg id="78">According to the provisions of Section 49 of Act No 222/2004 Z, the payer can. z. deduct VAT if the tax is applied to the acquisition of goods domestically from another Member State in accordance with the provisions of Sections 11 and 11a of this Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">Triangular business is understood according to Section 17 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll., or Section 45 of Act No. 222/2004 Z. z. a transaction concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States, the subject of which is the supply of the same goods between the three.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intracommunity transactions mean the supply and acquisition of goods between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="81">The total volumes of intracommunity transactions between the Czech Republic and SR are shown in the table below.</seg>
<seg id="82">VIES</seg>
<seg id="83">In order to control the application of the VAT exemption right to intracommunity supplies of goods, a system of exchange of VAT information has been established within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="84">It includes an electronic VIES system that allows EU tax administrations to check whether the supplier has been entitled to exempt taxable transactions from VAT and vice versa whether the purchaser has properly declared and taxed the goods acquired.</seg>
<seg id="85">The VIES information system is not centralised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="86">Each Member State shall develop its own VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="87">National systems work on a common principle and are interconnected through the EU Common Communication Network (CCN); see diagram below).</seg>
<seg id="88">In the Czech Republic, the VIES system was connected to the automated tax information system (hereinafter referred to as "ADIS"), in SR to the application software of the tax information system (hereinafter referred to as "APV DIS").</seg>
<seg id="89">These systems are used by financial and tax authorities as technical support for executive and management activities in the administration of taxes and charges.</seg>
<seg id="90">International administrative cooperation</seg>
<seg id="91">Through international administrative cooperation, the tax administration of each EU Member State receives information on tax entities that it would not be able to obtain on its own without such cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="92">The main objective of international administrative cooperation is to combat tax evasion and tax losses.</seg>
<seg id="93">Under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, each Member State, within its internal organisational structure, establishes a central unit in the field of administrative cooperation between EU Member States in the administration of VAT, the Central Liaison Office.</seg>
<seg id="94">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance - Central Financial and Tax Directorate, where the Department of International Cooperation in VAT Administration (hereinafter referred to as "MF Customs") has been established, performs the tasks resulting from international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="95">The function of the Customs Office in SR is carried out by the Tax Directorate of SR, Department of International Administrative Cooperation (hereinafter referred to as "DR Customs").</seg>
<seg id="96">These departments inter alia communicate with EU foreign administrations in particular in the field of information exchange within the VIES system, exchange of spontaneous information and information at the request of the EU tax administrations, coordination of multilateral (simultaneous) tax controls, verification of tax identification numbers (hereinafter referred to as "VAT creditors") in other EU Member States and communicate with the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to verify an intracommunity transaction or to obtain other information related to a particular tax entity, the financial and tax authorities send requests for information to the EU via the MF Customs and DR Customs.</seg>
<seg id="98">Through these requests, they receive information from the requested Member States that they can use to correct the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="99">Requests for information are sent mostly in electronic form between EU Member State Customs using the standardised SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="100">Selected control findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="101">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was focused mainly on the examination of selected intracommunity transactions between the two countries and on the level of use of information obtained through international cooperation by financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="102">The SAO, the Czech Republic requested the SAO to examine in 30 cases commercial transactions between 19 Czech and 25 Slovak tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="103">SAO SR requested the SAO, Czech Republic to examine in 10 cases commercial transactions between 7 Slovak and 10 Czech tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="104">The examination of intracommunity transactions revealed:</seg>
