<seg id="113">Through the SCAC form the Czech tax administrator requested an examination of the delivery of the technology line to SR totalling CZK 4,850 in the second quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="114">The tax procedure carried out in SR showed that only part of the technological line was supplied. The components totalling CZK 3,395 thousand were not delivered.</seg>
<seg id="115">The SAO SR found during the examination of this case that the VAT on the taxable transactions made was declared by the Slovak tax entity on the amount of CZK 4,850 in the VAT return (hereinafter referred to as "DAP") for the tax period 7/2004.</seg>
<seg id="116">The SAO, Czech Republic also found that the Czech taxpayer reported excessive VAT deduction of CZK 655 thousand for that quarter in its DAP, resulting from the application of the VAT deduction on the purchase of this technology line from another domestic payer.</seg>
<seg id="117">On the basis of the results of the investigation, the Czech Tax Office concluded that the Czech and Slovak tax entities established a business relationship for the purpose of unduly obtaining an excess VAT deduction, questioned the taxable transactions and did not recognise the Czech taxpayer's part of the right to deduct CZK 647 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="118">o</seg>
<seg id="119">In 2004, the Slovak tax administrator applied to the Czech taxpayer by means of the SCAC form for verification of the supply of goods (copying machines) in the value of SK 24,246 in December 2002.</seg>
