<seg id="135">The Slovak company supplied goods (woodpecker products) to an American company, which stored these goods in the Czech Republic in a free zone.</seg>
<seg id="136">The operator of this free zone was indicated on the invoices as the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="137">In 2004, for example, an American company purchased from a Slovak payer a wooden tile worth USD 57,600 (at a unit price of USD 100/unit), which it placed in a free zone.</seg>
<seg id="138">Subsequently, the company transferred the property rights to the goods to a Swiss company worth USD 14,400 (unit price USD 25/unit) and the goods were exported back to the SR.</seg>
<seg id="139">The goods were not unloaded in the Czech Republic, but left the area of the free zone on the same means of transport.</seg>
<seg id="140">The Slovak tax administrator initiated tax checks on the supplier of goods for suspected carousel transactions in the various tax years 2004 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="141">Examination of transactions was requested by the Czech local tax administrators using several SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="142">The individual replies gradually created a picture of business and confirmed the involvement of stakeholders from the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in carousel business.</seg>
<seg id="143">The SAO, the Czech Republic, in cooperation with the SAO SR, found that these trade relations deliberately resulted in a gradual multiple depreciation of the value of goods.</seg>
<seg id="144">On the basis of the information obtained, the Tax Directorate of SR concluded that in this case carousel trade is free pricing (i.e. the import of underserved goods and its overvaluation by domestic companies located in the chain between the importer and the exporter), which is not a breach of the VAT Act in the SR.</seg>
<seg id="145">In the current legislation, the excessive deduction of VAT to export companies cannot be avoided as they fulfil all the conditions of the Act on VAT exemption.</seg>
