<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">On the basis of international cooperation, compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT and the use of the VIES system to exchange information between EU Member States have been examined, in particular in monitoring the application of the VAT exemption claim.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation made it possible to examine selected intracommunitary transactions between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="371">By examining the selected transactions, it was found that, on the basis of an international exchange of information, the tax administrations of both countries detected cases of companies carrying out fictitious intracommunitarian commercial transactions in order to obtain excessive VAT deductions, as well as cases where the purchasers did not grant VAT on received supplies of goods at the correct amount.</seg>
<seg id="372">The examination also identified differences in the processing and use of VIES data by the tax administrations of the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also highlighted problems caused by different reporting of data on intracommunity supplies and acquisitions of goods in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">A harmonisation of the conditions for reporting such data within the EU would make the control activities of the national tax administrations more effective.</seg>
<seg id="375">By examining the procedure of the financial or tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system, it was found that the financial or tax authorities did not make sufficient use of all the possibilities of the VIES system and the relevant legal authorisations.</seg>
<seg id="376">It was also found that the VIES system did not in all cases provide up-to-date information on the supply of goods and the validity of the registration of tax entities for VAT.</seg>
<seg id="377">SAO SR compared data on the incidence of erroneous data in the SH, processed before the start of the inspection, with data processed after the completion of the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="378">It was clear from the comparison of these data that the SAO SR control had an effect not only on the reduction of the number of SHs with the erroneously mentioned TS, but also on the reduction of the number of unrepaired errors in the SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In the event of irregularities in the reported SAO data, the SAO requested the tax authorities to carry out local investigations and, where appropriate, to carry out tax checks.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, the Czech Republic did not have such an option under the applicable legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">The knowledge gained by the control action showed that VIES provided tax administrations with the basic information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intracommunity transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">Given that there remains scope for tax evasion in this area, there is a need for increased attention to be paid to intracommunity transactions when administering VAT.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was prepared in the Czech, English and Slovak languages and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the President of the Czech Audit Office of the Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
