<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material gives an overview of the progress and results of the parallel control actions carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the General Audit Office of the Republic of Slovenia, which were focused on the area of value added management and excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="4">Cooperation between the Supreme Audit Offices of both countries was carried out on the basis of a cooperation agreement in the control activity concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The theme of parallel control actions was selected in view of the fact that indirect taxes contribute significantly to the revenues of the national budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of the value added tax, enabling the excess deduction to be recovered, provides room for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise duties, especially on tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean high profits for those who escape taxation by illegally selling these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue comprehensively throughout the European Union, a working group of VAT Working Groups has been set up by the supreme audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union, with the highest audit authorities of both countries actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefits of the audits can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but in particular in the joint effort to identify problems in the management of indirect taxes in order to limit the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The experience and knowledge gained will be used in the framework of planned controls on indirect taxes, mainly aimed at involving the tax administrators of both countries in the VIES system, which can control the movement of goods between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the control of the administration of value added tax and excise duties for 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Control number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Control of the tax administrator's procedures for the administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="18">On 11.2. 2004, a Contract for cooperation in control activities was concluded between the Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the Czech Audit Office of the Republic (SAO SR). The subject of the contract was cooperation in the implementation of the parallel control actions "Value Added Tax and Excise Duty," included in the SAO's control plan for 2004 under No 04/07, and "Audit of the SAO's practice of the tax administrator in relation to the collection, control and enforcement of value added tax and other taxes," included in the SAO's control activity plan under No. 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="19">Cooperation consisted of the exchange of information to the extent provided for in the Treaty and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">In the contract, both parties undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the customs database and from the files of tax entities maintained by the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the contracting parties could not obtain when controlling the application of value added tax and excise duties on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the relevant state.</seg>
<seg id="21">The checks were carried out in parallel between January and August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic"), the control was carried out by the state budget department and the territorial unions of southern Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited persons were the Directorate-General of Customs and the 12 selected tax offices: Tax Office for Prague 1, Tax Office for Prague 3, Tax Office in České Budějovice, Tax Office in Frýdk-Místek, Tax Office in Hodonín, Tax Office in Jihlava, Tax Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, Tax Office in Kroměříz, Financial Office in Písko</seg>
<seg id="24">The inspection on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter "SR") was carried out by the SAO Section of Tax and Customs in cooperation with Exposures of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">Tax department Bratislava for selected tax entities, Tax department Bratislava III, Tax department Trnava, Tax department Pu-breeding, Tax department Banská Bystrica I, Tax department Liptovský Mikuláš, Tax department Žilina I, Tax department Žilina II, Tax department Košice I and</seg>
<seg id="26">Control objective</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the audits was to examine the fulfilment of the obligations of the financial and/or tax offices and customs offices in the administration of value added tax and excise duties, focusing on the collection of these taxes in the import and export of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of SR and their subsequent verification in tax returns on the relevant financial and tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="32">Within the framework of international cooperation of the SAO, the SAO has transferred from the customs database of the Czech Republic 22,206 items of the Uniform Customs Declarations (hereinafter referred to as the "JCD") on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and, conversely, the SAO has transmitted to the SAO from the customs database SR 30,221.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison was made between the printed JCD items from the Czech Customs Database and the SR Customs Database.</seg>
<seg id="34">Out of 5,883 selected JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic, 43% of related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Of the 12 343 selected JCD items from the SR customs database, a total of 26% of the related JCD items were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">Based on the unassigned items of the JCD, the financial and/or tax offices included a selection of files of tax entities for which the reported imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic and the financial and tax authorities, the implementation of reported imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified in the territory of the other State.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO SR carried out a joint pilot inspection at the border crossing point Old Hrozenkov - Drietoma, where both parties cooperated closely in verifying the accuracy of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="39">The audit did not identify deficiencies in the record of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation enabled the examination of trade transactions between trading partners from both countries and highlighted weaknesses in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="42">In the field of international cooperation, the SAO and SAO control focused on imports and exports of alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their components, or other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">On the basis of a review of the tax records of selected financial and tax authorities, the SAO requested verification of the realization of exports of goods reported at 40 JCD totalling CZK 15,301,093 and the SAO SR to verify exports at a statistical value of SK 56,989.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO have identified, inter alia, the following:</seg>
<seg id="45">- commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the SR,</seg>
<seg id="46">- error in entering data into customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- for certain exports from the Czech Republic, the corresponding imports to the SR have not been demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="48">In these cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of undue application of value added tax deductions,</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax entities have failed to comply with certain obligations laid down by law in the reporting of imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- weaknesses have been identified in the activities of the financial and tax offices in the administration of value added tax and excise duties and in their cooperation with the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of value added tax and excise duties, international trade will continue to need to be addressed in order to effectively minimise tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the activities of tax administrations in the administration of value added tax.</seg>
<seg id="53">The basis for effective control of excise duties is control of the circulation of documents, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information on import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the situation in the field of value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value Added Tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (VAT) was levied by the financial and/or tax authorities on taxable transactions effected domestically and by the customs authorities on importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The tax revenues were due to the difference between the tax liability collected and the excess VAT deductions recovered.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenues at customs offices were given by the amount of their tax collected.</seg>
<seg id="59">The tax collected by the customs authorities, in accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, was reflected in the tax deductions applied to the financial and tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most financial and tax authorities, excessive VAT deductions exceeded tax obligations.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the flagship taxes in terms of revenue of the state budget, as it accounted for approximately 31% of the tax revenue of the Czech state budget in 2003 and approximately 42% of the tax revenue of the state budget of SR.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic reached CZK 162.9 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="63">The tax and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions refunded totalled CZK 231.4 billion.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total VAT collection in Slovakia totalled SK 83.8 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="65">Tax and customs authorities collected SK $187.0 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions were reimbursed totalling SK $103.2 billion.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise duties</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise duties (SPD) was carried out by the relevant financial and/or tax authorities and the customs authorities when importing products subject to SPD.</seg>
<seg id="68">SpD's share of state budget tax revenues in the Czech Republic was approximately 16% in 2003 and about 19% in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total collection of SPD collected in the Czech Republic by the financial and customs authorities in 2003 amounted to CZK 85.6 billion and in the Slovak Republic amounted to Sk 38.0 billion.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Progress of the control action</seg>
<seg id="71">Cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">The first stage included a comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia. In the second stage, the results of this comparison were used to verify the implementation of selected commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of the control action</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel checks of VAT and SPD was presented at a working meeting of representatives of SAO and SAO SR in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">A coordination meeting was held in November 2003, where the selection of commodities - the types of goods which posed a significant risk in compliance with customs and tax rules - was agreed, inter alia: - alcohol and spirits, tariff items Nos 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, tariff items No.2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff subheadings No 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, tariff subheadings No 8525,20,91,8525,20,99,8529,90,40.</seg>
<seg id="77">Both parties agreed that the selection of tax entities for inspection will be carried out: (a) from unassigned items found by comparison of exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and SR, (b) from entities carrying out imports and exports on a regular or one-off basis in large volumes, (c) based on findings from controls carried out by selected financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, the JCD item assignment mechanism registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and SR was tested on the sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, part of the exports from the Czech Republic were compared with imports into the Slovak Republic for 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Undenatured ethyl alcohol with an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol. or more; ethyl alcohol and other distillates denatured, of any alcoholic strength,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Undenatured ethyl alcohol with an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol; distillates, liqueurs and other spirit drinks,</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unprocessed tobacco; tobacco waste,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars (whether or not with cut-off ends), cigarillos and cigarettes of tobacco or tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other tobacco products and tobacco substitutes; homogenised or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and punishments (essence),</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmitters containing reception equipment: For cellular network (mobile phones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmitters containing reception equipment: Other,</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling within subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">The JCD entries from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia were assigned to each other on the basis of the conformity of the individual paragraphs of the JCD (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration mark of the vehicle carrying the cargo, date of crossing the national border, tariff entry, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are presented in the following tables and graphs.</seg>
<seg id="92">Inter alia, the fact that commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides made it difficult to assign individual imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic declared in one export JCD were declared in the Slovak Republic for several import JCDs, or the export JCD had a different number of items from the import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that affected the success of the assignment were the different composition of data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, as well as the time shift between the registration of exports in the customs database of one country and the registration of corresponding imports in the customs database of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples at the audited financial and tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was given to certain tax entities that made imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, which could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, some tax entities were collected to verify the transactions reported in the VAT tax returns for which data on imports and exports between the Czech Republic and SR were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">Pilot control at the border crossing point Old Hrozenkov-Drietoma</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing for pilot inspection was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of unassigned JCD items in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and SR.</seg>
<seg id="100">On the basis of a bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and SR, the use of checkpoints has been introduced at border crossing points between the Czech Republic and SR since 1.6.1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate customs and tax evasion as far as possible, to ensure an overview of the movements of commercial goods in the customs area and to create conditions for cross-comparison of customs records.</seg>
<seg id="102">The joint pilot inspection was carried out between 8.3.2004 and 26.3.2004 and aimed at verifying this customs control system.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for the use of checkpoints at the Old Hrozenkov-Drietoma border crossing point:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Weighing the vehicle, issuing the check sheet and giving it to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Weaning of the vehicle in the indicated sector in the parking lot.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs discussion in the check-in hall by the Police of the Czech Republic, the Police of Slovakia, the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The check-in process was confirmed by individual components by stamping on the checklist.</seg>
<seg id="108">3) Attachment of the vehicle to the physical inspection area.</seg>
<seg id="109">Presentation of the certificate of inspection, JCD, or other documents to a customs official, as appropriate - checking the execution of all the prescribed acts and documents.</seg>
<seg id="110">Carrying out physical checks by the relevant constituents.</seg>
<seg id="111">Release of the vehicle from the customs compartment.</seg>
<seg id="112">Pozru: When the goods were imported into the Czech Republic, weighted vehicles were carried out directly by the staff of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When the goods were imported into the SR, the weighted vehicles were carried out by staff of the authorised legal person.</seg>
<seg id="114">The vehicles were registered in computer records after weighing.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1 Control sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="117">The control sample was selected on the basis of an analysis of records from the customs database of Czech exports in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the export control sample is set out in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">Check sheets and their registration Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="120">When exporting from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic, control sheets were issued and registered by the Slovak Customs Administration.</seg>
<seg id="121">The customs administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these checklists in the electronic database of exports.</seg>
<seg id="122">Of the 453 items of the JCD, SAO SR tracked 256 cases of imports into the SR according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and Slovakia. The remaining 197 items of the JCD were identified by the SAO SR in cooperation with the staff of the Drietoma Border Customs Crossing Point.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from SR to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exporting from SR to the Czech Republic, checklists were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">Out of a total of 339 items of JCD of the selected SAO control sample in cooperation with the staff of the border customs crossing point, Staré Hrozenkov assigned the corresponding registration numbers of the checkpoints to 295 items of JCD.</seg>
<seg id="126">The other 44 cases were identified in their register by the Drietoma Border Customs Crossing Point workers and confirmed the export of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="127">The audit of the SAO and SAO SR did not identify deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the border crossing point of Stará Hrozenkov-Drietoma.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4 Selected control findings when verifying business transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">Within the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia was verified on the basis of customs administrations and financial and tax offices in the territory of the other state.</seg>
<seg id="130">For selected tax entities:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia,</seg>
<seg id="132">- fulfilment of the legal conditions for the application of the VAT deduction on importation, the reimbursement of excessive VAT deduction and the application of the VAT exemption on export.</seg>
<seg id="133">Verifying business transactions revealed:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. SAO SR requested verification of the realization of the export of alcohol in the statistical value of 56,989 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified corresponding imports in the customs database of the Czech Republic at a statistical value of 42,624 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="136">2. The Company involved in the import and export of photographic equipment and accessories applied an excessive VAT deduction of CZK 3,740,664 for the month of December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to check the reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO selected 3 JCDs (16 items) at a statistical value of CZK 1,274,822.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO SR has identified 3 corresponding import JCDs (17 items) at a statistical value of SK 1 724 321.</seg>
<seg id="139">VAT was paid in SR to the competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. The Company, which was mainly engaged in the business of optical equipment, applied a total excess VAT deduction of CZK 4,1,36,000 higher than the tax liability in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="141">To verify the reported business activity, the SAO selected an export JCD (32 items) with a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO SR found that this JCD corresponds to the import JCD (12 items) with a statistical value of 9,653,827 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="143">VAT was paid in SR to the competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. The company engaged in, inter alia, the purchase of goods for resale and sale did not declare any exports of goods in the tax returns submitted in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 totalled CZK 3,439,888.</seg>
<seg id="146">On this basis, the SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) in total statistical value of CZK 669,839 for verification.</seg>
<seg id="147">SAO SR has identified 5 corresponding import JCDs (5 items) at a statistical value of 1,012,656 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="148">The audit of the SAO SR at the competent tax office demonstrated the implementation of the declared imports and payment of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The Company, which included the purchase of goods for resale and the sale, production, installation and repair of electrical machinery and equipment, reported exports of goods worth CZK 12,966,706 in 2002 in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, in 2002 the total value of exports was CZK 14,474,381.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCDs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO SR has identified in the customs database SR 13 JCD (50 items) the statistical value of 3 621 370 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="153">The SLOVAK customs database failed to identify the corresponding import JCD to 4 export JCDs (9 items) totalling CZK 399,776.</seg>
<seg id="154">The competent tax authority in the SR verified these imports with the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity listed on the JCD as an importer in the SR stated in the local investigation that imports declared on the Czech export JCD were not realised.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO SR therefore requested the local competent tax authority to carry out a tax check on VAT and corporate tax for the 2002 and 2003 tax years.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. According to the Customs Database of the Czech Republic, the company involved in importing and selling cigarettes exported tobacco stickers with a statistical value of CZK 7,338,199 in 2002 and a statistical value of CZK 12,228,545 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="158">No exports were recorded in the 2002 and 2003 VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected 5 export JCDs (5 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598 for verification.</seg>
<seg id="160">To 4 export JCDs (4 items) totalling CZK 2,246,860, the SAO SR identified in the customs database SR 7 JCD (7 items) a statistical value of SK 2,919,514.</seg>
<seg id="161">The export JCD (1 item) totalling CZK 224,738 could not be assigned to the corresponding imports in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The software company did not declare exports of goods in the VAT returns for 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 and 2003 totalled CZK 1,630,198.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected 9 JCDs (9 items) for verification in the total statistical value of CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the customs database of SR SAO SR, 8 JCDs (8 items) identified a statistical value of 915 601 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="166">The export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 68 286 could not be assigned corresponding imports in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In these cases, the customs database SR failed to identify the corresponding imports to 6 JCDs at a statistical value of CZK 692,800.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- on 2 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic with a statistical value of CZK 293,024, the customs database of SR failed to identify the corresponding import JCD (see paragraphs 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error in entering data into the customs database, it was not possible to identify certain registered imports, e.g. in cases where the name of the importer was missing or an error in the tax identification number ("TIER").</seg>
<seg id="171">It is therefore not possible to state with certainty that these exports did not materialise.</seg>
<seg id="172">- on 4 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic, imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic were not proven at a statistical value of CZK 399,776 (see paragraph 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, suspicion of fictitious export of goods for the purpose of undue application of the VAT deduction is justified.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services under the control of selected financial and tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of tax authorities on imports and exports of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between the financial and customs authorities, the files of the tax entities were collected at the audited financial and tax offices in accordance with the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1st tax entities were collected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia: (a) with the highest import volume, (b) with the highest amount of VAT, (c) with the highest export volume,</seg>
<seg id="178">Tax entities were collected from the financial and/or tax offices according to the amount: (a) VAT deductions applied on importation, (b) excessive VAT deductions applied, (c) the right to refund the SPD, (d) the VAT exemption applied on export,</seg>
<seg id="179">3 tax entities where the tax check has been carried out.</seg>
<seg id="180">Sampling was carried out irrespective of the country of destination, focusing on risk commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Control findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risk commodities in 2002 and 2003 is given in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Control of the selected sample at the financial offices</seg>
<seg id="184">The SAO focused on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure of the financial authorities to verify the accuracy of VAT declared,</seg>
<seg id="186">- cooperation between the tax authorities and the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparison of data from the customs database with the JCD database at the tax offices with a view to comparing the declared value, applying the correct VAT rate following the classification of goods or services, etc. comparison of data on the JCD and accompanying invoices with data in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- a comparison of VAT return data on transactions effected and received from abroad with data in the JCD database at the tax offices or in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="189">- the method of verifying the right to VAT exemption when goods or services are exported abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- a comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services provided declared in VAT returns with the data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at the tax authorities contained only records of those imports and exports for which tax entities were obliged to place imports or exports on the tax return.</seg>
<seg id="192">The audited financial offices examined the files of tax entities which showed total imports totalling CZK 60,396,379 thousand in VAT returns in the years 2002 and 2003 and corresponding VAT totalling CZK 12,644,052 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="193">In addition, the records of tax entities reporting exports totalling CZK 47,33,111 were checked in the 2002 and 2003 tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="194">Tax entities for which imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were examined, according to the Czech Customs Database in 2002 and 2003 imports into the Czech Republic from the Slovak Republic totalling CZK 3,759,352 thousand, VAT of CZK 767,607 and exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of CZK 1,989,090 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="195">The differences found between the records in the JCD database at the tax offices and in the customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- JCD items missing from the customs database of the Czech Republic were requested directly by the Directorate-General of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- for JCD items missing from the database of financial authorities, it has been verified that they are not cancelled documents,</seg>
<seg id="198">- for items of the JCD for which different values were found between the customs database of the Czech Republic and the database of the financial authorities, they were requested by the Directorate-General of Customs of the Czech Republic to the relevant JCD in writing, including the invoices attached.</seg>
<seg id="199">The examination revealed that the JCD database at the tax offices did not contain, for example, records of import JCD totalling CZK 3,622 thousand and export JCD records totalling CZK 9,359 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Differences detected</seg>
<seg id="201">By comparing the JCD database at the tax authorities and the accumulated tax liabilities for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT returns of the selected sample, the following differences were found:</seg>
<seg id="202">Differences in values were mainly due to:</seg>
<seg id="203">- A time shift between the realization of imports and the application of the right to deduct VAT charged on imports of goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The taxpayer could claim a deduction for the importation of goods within 3 years of the end of the tax period during which the goods were placed under the relevant procedure or, in the case of temporary importation, no later than 3 years after the end of the tax period during which the scheme was terminated.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time shift between the realisation of exports and the moment when the tax entity received the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The taxpayer was obliged to provide information on exports made exempt from the obligation to apply the output tax on the VAT return at the earliest for the tax period in which the goods left the country, provided that it also had the tax document which was the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- Failure to fulfil the obligations of tax entities to report imports and exports in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, tax entities did not provide correct data on imports and exports on VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">As tax entities did not have to attach the JCD lists to the VAT returns submitted, it was difficult to check the right to deduct VAT or VAT exemption from the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Synergies between financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">In the audited period, import or export duties and VAT were repaid or remitted at the discretion of the customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="212">Tax entities were obliged by law to reduce the previously claimed VAT deduction entitlement by the amount of tax refunded by the customs office in the tax return for the period during which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legislation provided for the sending of information on changes in customs duty and VAT to tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax authorities received this information, but irregularly or with considerable time delays and only from certain customs offices.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited tax authority did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information on the changes in the amount of customs duty and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the information needed to check compliance with the legal obligation on tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, the customs authorities refunded more than 319 million VAT. CZK and in 2003 in the amount of over 398 million. CZK.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit highlighted persistent shortcomings in the activities of tax administrations, some systemic errors in the cooperation of tax authorities with customs authorities and the failure to fulfil certain obligations of taxpayers filing VAT and SPD tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="219">When administering VAT and SPD, weaknesses were identified in particular in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="220">a) when VAT registrations were cancelled, the fulfilment of the payers' obligation to pay VAT on commercial assets registered or to be registered at the date of the cancellation of the registration for which the payer applied the tax deduction was only rarely verified,</seg>
<seg id="221">b) the tax authorities did not consistently use the possibility of tax checks or local investigations.</seg>
<seg id="222">This has in some cases underestimated the legitimacy of the right to deduct VAT,</seg>
<seg id="223">(c) the official records and oral protocols did not contain all the necessary data to demonstrate the legitimacy of the excessive VAT deductions applied,</seg>
<seg id="224">d) the tax authorities did not adequately verify imports and exports declared in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Control findings in SR</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Check of selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">For the selected sample, the SAO has verified or the tax office has carried out a tax check for the 2002 and 2003 tax years.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analysing tax returns and refund requests for selected tax entities of the SAO SR, the Tax Office requested that the relevant JCDs attest to imports and exports, invoices and proof of payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, SAO SR checked whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs database of imports and exports and fulfilled the decisive facts and legal conditions by applying the deduction of the entry tax on imports, the refund of the excess VAT deduction, the application of the export tax exemption and the refund of the SPD.</seg>
<seg id="230">SAO SR verified selected cases of imports and exports of goods between SR and CR in 10 audited tax offices in the structure according to the JCD headings and the sum of statistical values listed in the table below.</seg>
<seg id="231">Total imports at a statistical value of 856,2 million were checked. SK, representing 5,11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic into the SROV.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were checked at a total statistical value of 176 million. Sk, which represents 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from SR to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">In addition, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white equipment, packaging equipment and software) from the EU States to the Slovak Republic were checked for a total statistical value of 532.8 million. Sk.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Synergies between tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO SR found irregularities at the tax offices between data recorded in the SR customs database and data reported in specific VAT returns, such as:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax entities (natural persons) indicated in their tax returns imports of goods totalling Sk 1 589 261, on the basis of which they claimed the refund of excessive VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">In the local investigations carried out at the initiative of the SAO SR, the tax authorities were unable to prove to the tax office the legitimacy of the application of the entry tax by the relevant evidence of the importation and payment of VAT,</seg>
<seg id="238">- the tax entity (s. r. o.) in the tax return for the tax year January 2003 declared the taxable transactions received in the value of 77 167 576 Sk, the export of goods in the value of 18 006 041 Sk and applied an excess VAT deduction of 17 157 101 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="239">The 2003 VAT returns show that the difference between the purchase and export volumes of Sk 59 161 535 incurred in January 2003 was not offset throughout 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the abovementioned cases, the SAO SR requested the competent tax authorities to carry out a tax check on the excessive VAT deductions applied.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax entity (s. r. o.) for the tax period January to June 2002 indicated in the VAT returns the export of goods totalling 87 199 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="242">The verification in the SR customs database revealed that the tax entity carried out exports at a statistical value of Sk 296 747 during that period.</seg>
<seg id="243">The Tax Office carried out multiple local investigations at the company's head office, finding that the company manager (a UK citizen) had travelled and that the company had left the leased premises without terminating the lease in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of auditing the SAO, the tax administrator filed a complaint with the law enforcement authorities on suspicion of a non-tax offence.</seg>
<seg id="245">On the basis of the results of the audit at selected tax offices, the SAO notes that the main problems in the administration and control of VAT and SPD occurred mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- not making use of the possibility of carrying out VAT tax checks on problematic tax entities, in particular in cases where excessive VAT deductions are applied,</seg>
<seg id="247">- the tax control protocols did not contain an inventory of the audited documents</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCD when importing and exporting goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient verification of reported imports and exports of goods in tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="250">- lengthy management of tax administrations in the issuing of decisions, in particular in the context of the assessment procedure, as well as the termination of the right to sanction,</seg>
<seg id="251">- non-compliance with the legal conditions for granting deferrals,</seg>
<seg id="252">- the non-offsetting of VAT arrears within the time limit for the refund of the excess VAT deduction,</seg>
<seg id="253">- insufficient use of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">Based on the audit of the SAO's deficiencies, the competent tax authorities requested VAT to be reviewed, focusing on the justification of the excessive VAT deductions applied to 14 tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="255">Measures have been taken at all audited tax offices to remedy the deficiencies identified, which the SAO will monitor and control.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation enabled the examination of trade transactions between trading partners from both countries and highlighted weaknesses in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">The checks also resulted in the identification of persistent deficiencies in the fulfilment of the obligations of VAT and SPD payers, in the activities of the financial and tax authorities, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs authorities, which ultimately reduced the efficiency and efficiency of tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="259">The lessons learned also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have basic data on imports and exports from the customs database of the Czech Republic. In the SR, there is no similar system of transmission of information on imports and exports of goods between the customs and tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of VAT and SPD administration was not identical due to different legislation and conditions in the territory of both States.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from the information obtained from the customs administration of the Czech Republic and from the supporting documents available at the audited financial offices. SAO SR verified the execution of commercial transactions from documents of tax entities requested through tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="262">If irregularities were found, he asked the tax authorities to carry out tax checks.</seg>
<seg id="263">The parallel VAT and SPD checks carried out assessed the state of administration of these taxes in the period prior to accession to the European Union and highlighted the need for further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further deepened in the control of the activities of the financial and tax authorities in connection with the adoption of the new VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of a summary report.</seg>
<seg id="266">This declaration must be made by all VAT payers who have delivered goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrations are obliged to enter data from summary reports into the VAT Information Exchange System (VIES), to which tax administrations from the Member States of the European Union have access.</seg>
<seg id="268">The financial and/or tax authorities are then able to compare these data with those given in the tax returns filed.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is also used to verify the validity of VAT registrants, to verify the lawfulness of the VAT exemption applied when goods are delivered to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel control actions showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these control actions will be confronted with the outputs of the forthcoming control actions, which will focus, among other things, on screening the VIES system to prevent tax evasion in so-called "intracommunity supplies."</seg>
<seg id="272">Given the importance of VAT and SPD for budgetary revenues, control activities need to be focused primarily on monitoring and identifying risk areas in order to limit the scope for tax evasion in indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and the Chairman of the Czech Audit Office.</seg>
</p>
