<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of inspections at asylum facilities in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State property and funds intended to safeguard the activities of the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Control Action No. 04/23 "State Property and Funds for Securing the Activities of the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior"</seg>
<seg id="4">Control Action No 15/2004 "Control of the economy with assets and financial provisions intended for asylum and temporary refuge in the Slovak Republic"</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the phenomena of a global nature and has become an inseparable part of the current development phase of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">Its main cause is the escape of citizens from the country of origin or last permanent residence from persecution, in particular for reasons of racial, religious, national, political, as well as the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">They aim to gain asylum and integration into society, especially in one of Europe's advanced democratic countries.</seg>
<seg id="9">The large group is also composed of foreigners whose reasons for migration are unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The adoption of the 1951 Geneva Agreement and the 1967 New York Protocol on the Status of Refugees, by which the governments of the signatory countries undertook to apply them in their foreign-policy orientation, has already produced concrete principles for helping refugees.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federative Republics ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">Both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue after the division in 1993 by continuing to implement the adopted international documents and confirmed their binding in the framework of national legislation by means of a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both republics have enshrined asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the International Audit Office of the Republic were focused on the asylum process and related issues, the results of which are contained in the joint final report.</seg>
<seg id="16">Cooperation between the Supreme Audit Offices of both countries was carried out on the basis of the "Surveillance Cooperation Treaty" ("the Treaty") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">In the Treaty, both Parties undertook to provide each other with information on the legislation governing asylum procedures in the State of the other Party, selected statistics on the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The aim of the parallel control action was to identify the same problem lines and highlight the implications for the area of population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">Cooperation consisted of the alignment of the programme of control actions, the exchange of information to the extent provided for by the Treaty and the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the checks.</seg>
<seg id="20">The first joint meeting, which took place between 5.4 and 7.4.2004, established the same categories of controlled issues and control procedures for the preparation of control actions.</seg>
<seg id="21">The second meeting, which took place between 28.6 and 30.6. 2004, clarified the common points for the control action programme.</seg>
<seg id="22">The third joint meeting, which took place during the control action from 8.11 to 10.11.2004, exchanged experiences from ongoing inspections.</seg>
<seg id="23">The forms of outputs from the checks have been specified and the structure and content of the joint final report drawn up at the last joint meeting on 14 February to 17 February 2005 have been provisionally established.</seg>
<seg id="24">The checks were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, inspectors of the Department of Defence and Security and selected territorial unions carried out the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="26">The audited persons were the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "MV") and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as "SUZ").</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic carried out the control of the defence section, the army and the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="28">The audited body was the Migration Department of the Ministry of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "Ministry of Education").</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period was 2001, 2002, 2003 (the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistics for a longer period of time are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Recapitulation of control results</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Evaluation of control activities</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of parallel checks was: - asylum process, - asylum facilities, - management of funds and state property, - internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of experience between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Czech Audit Office of the Czech Republic took place during the preparation and implementation of the control actions.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange enabled a more thorough evaluation of the evidence submitted, analysing the causes of the detected differences in securing the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">This made it possible to concentrate on the critical problems affecting the activities of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">Ultimately, this positively affected the quality of the performance of the control activity.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with European Union documents ("the EU") has been the subject of evaluation reports by the European Commission on the preparedness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">The adoption of legislation on this issue is continuing after both countries have joined the EU with a view to further harmonisation with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants is on a steadily growing trend, with a significant increase in applicants in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic provide financial and material security for asylum seekers within the meaning of international agreements.</seg>
<seg id="44">The national budget of both countries allocates the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the national budget of both countries is mainly influenced by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until the granting or granting of asylum and also by the state of health of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">The amount of some selected doses is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic established asylum facilities in which they gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of the parties to asylum proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="48">Asylum facilities provide asylum seekers with accommodation, food, healthcare and basic material and hygiene supplies during their stay.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, leisure activities are organised and conditions for cultural and sporting activities are created for applicants.</seg>
<seg id="50">Asylum facilities include reception centres and residential centres, in the Czech Republic and integration centres.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cost per day depends on the Centre's occupancy and equipment and is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is in principle stabilised.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is projected to increase by almost 1,000 seats in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create conditions for applicants, which are expected to continue to apply the Dublin Convention for years to come.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the highest proportion of approved budgetary expenditure was spent on security of services. The decisive expenditure of this item was expenditure on accommodation and catering of applicants in asylum facilities operated on the basis of a contract, expenditure on healthcare provided to asylum seekers and the cost of a permanent security service ensuring the protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work carried out and premiums contributed significantly to the overall expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of migration policy and the asylum process was marked by many budgetary measures that addressed legitimate requirements related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditure on wages, salaries and premiums, expenditure on materials and services and expenditure on security services contributed decisively to the absorption of current expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the audits in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic highlighted some similar shortcomings that did not have a major impact on the financial management and management of state property.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were weaknesses in particular in the use of State budget resources contrary to the purpose for which they were determined by the State Budget Act when current expenditure covered actions having the character of technical evaluation of long-term tangible assets.</seg>
<seg id="61">The Accounting Act in the area of inventory and non-compliance with the accounting curriculum was also violated.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies in the handling of state property were also identified when it was left for use by another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">Failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes in land registry data violated the Land Registry Act and leaving waste for disposal to a person who was not a person entitled to waste management violated the Waste Act.</seg>
<seg id="64">In the Slovak Republic, shortcomings in the provision of disproportionately high reserves for the consumption of electricity and natural gas, deficiencies in public procurement and the management of State property were also identified when its records were not adequately secured and the method of disposal of unnecessary assets was not proven.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system was ensured in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic within the meaning of the generally binding legislation governing the way financial control is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="66">The submitted written dossier did not identify deficiencies.</seg>
<seg id="67">Despite some deficiencies identified, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Czech Republic have positively assessed the procedure of the SUZ and the MU in providing services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Based on the knowledge gained during the inspection, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic's Supervisory Authority note that despite a significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the relevant organisational units of both countries have managed the tasks associated with the care of asylum seekers at the appropriate level.</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is functional and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the audit were discussed with interested statutory representatives of the relevant organizational units of the state on the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the inspection, we recommend that positive methodological experience from control be used in other joint control actions within the framework of international cooperation of supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="72">3. Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, asylum law is based on the 1951 Geneva Convention (the Refugee Status Convention followed by the 1967 New York Protocol).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legislation was implemented by Act No. 498/1990 Coll., on refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum and Amending Act No. 83/1991 Coll., on the Police of the Czech Republic, has been effective in the Czech Republic since 1 January 2000.</seg>
<seg id="76">This Act was amended five times (Act No. 2/2002 Coll., Act No. 217/2002 Coll., Act No. 320/2002 Coll., Act No. 519/2002 Coll. and Act No. 222/2003 Coll.).</seg>
<seg id="77">Two other amendments to Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, are currently in the legislative process and the adoption of further amendments will be linked to European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">At the time of the Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on asylum, asylum was part of the third pillar of the EU and asylum documents were binding political documents.</seg>
<seg id="79">The adoption of this law already sought to make it as compatible as possible with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="80">A major change for asylum policy within the EU was the shift of asylum from the 3rd to the 1st pillar, when asylum law became part of Community law from 1.5. 1999 on the basis of the Treaty of Amsterdam.</seg>
<seg id="81">This shift has created the need to create appropriate legislation, i.e. to create legal instruments in the appropriate legal obligation.</seg>
<seg id="82">The compatibility of Czech asylum law with EU documents has been the subject of regular evaluation reports by the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="83">Key Community regulations in the field of asylum were adopted shortly before or after the Czech Republic entered the EU and their transposition period at the time of Supreme Audit Office inspection, the Czech Republic has not yet expired.</seg>
<seg id="84">After their implementation into the Czech legal order, the Czech Republic will be obliged to notify the European Commission how it transposed.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Slovak Republic, the procedure of state authorities in the procedure for granting refugee status and determining the obligations of foreigners who have applied for refugee status or who have been granted temporary refuge in the Slovak Republic was laid down by Law No 283/1995 of the National Council of the Slovak Republic with effect from 1.1.1996. z., the fugitive.</seg>
<seg id="86">Since 2003, the Refugee Act has been replaced by Act No 480/2002 Z. "on asylum and amending and supplementing certain laws, incorporating the harmonisation of the legislation of the Slovak Republic with the Council of Europe Directive 2001/55/ES from the 20.7.2001 on minimum standards for the granting of temporary protection in the event of a mass influx of displaced persons and on measures to promote a balance of efforts between Member States to recruit such persons and to endure the resulting consequences.</seg>
<seg id="87">Following two amendments to Act No 480/2002 of the Asylum Act 2003 and 2004, a third amendment was approved in early 2005, which means further harmonisation of the law of the Slovak Republic with EU legislation on migration and asylum.</seg>
<seg id="88">Its important elements are, for example, the obligation for asylum seekers to attend a course on the basis of Slovak language during their stay in the integration centre, the appointment of a guardian by the courts of unaccompanied foreigners if they are staying in the territory of the Slovak Republic without a legal representative, allowing applicants to enter into an employment relationship in certain circumstances, as specified in the amendment to the law.</seg>
<seg id="89">The harmonisation of Slovak Republic law with EU law in the field of migration and asylum process was assessed in regular reports by the European Commission on preparedness for accession of the Slovak Republic to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="90">In 2002, the report drew attention to the insufficient personnel capacity of the Ministry of Education, which did not correspond to the increased number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="91">4. Asylum process</seg>
<seg id="92">In the Czech Republic, since 1990, matters relating to refugees fall within the competence of the MV.</seg>
<seg id="93">With effect from 1.1.1996, the MV established the organisational arm of the SUZ State. This was due to the separation of State Administration's enforcement of the asylum procedure, which is carried out through the MV Department of Asylum and Migration Policy, from the provision of services to asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="94">The task of the SUZ is to provide accommodation, catering, health and other services to participants in asylum and asylum procedures.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Slovak Republic, they carry out decisive tasks in the field of the MA asylum process, in particular in terms of financial and material-technical security of the asylum process to the extent defined by specific regulations.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority tasks are issues related to the decision-making of aliens' applications for asylum in the I. the level of administrative management and the comprehensive operation of asylum facilities in the areas of accommodation, catering, health, financial and material security of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, it develops concepts for the migration policy of the state.</seg>
<seg id="98">Cooperation and support from the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has significantly affected the results achieved in the area of asylum system development in the Slovak Republic in recent years.</seg>
<seg id="99">His financial participation in the reconstruction of the asylum housing stock was of particular benefit.</seg>
<seg id="100">The UNHCR also co-financed social, cultural and sporting activities for applicants.</seg>
<seg id="101">4.1 Development of the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process</seg>
<seg id="102">The development of the number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic is shown in the chart.</seg>
<seg id="103">A significant increase occurred in 2001 due to the Kosovo crisis and in 2003 the number of refugees from Chechnya increased.</seg>
<seg id="104">For an overview of the results of the asylum procedure in the Czech Republic, see Table 1.</seg>
<seg id="105">A total of 394 cases were granted asylum in the audited period, including 83 in 2001, 103 in 2002 and 208 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="106">A total of 22,731 cases were not granted asylum in the audited period and 22,636 cases were terminated.</seg>
