<p>
<seg id="1">Joint report on parallel checks on expenditure on construction of the Prague - Dresden motorway</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">Without the existence of trans-European transport networks, a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe would be difficult to imagine.</seg>
<seg id="4">High-quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and raising the living standards of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of people and costs is an important task for government.</seg>
<seg id="6">This is a very demanding task both in organisational and technical terms and in financial terms.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts at sustainable mobility often and hard to find compromises with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">Construction of transport infrastructure, even with the necessary measures for the benefit of the environment, is financially demanding.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considered procedures and government decisions in the preparation and acquisition of transport buildings can generate significant savings in public financial resources that can be used differently for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the roles of the audit institutions is to actively look for shortcomings that have led to lower-than-achievable cost-effectiveness, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure on transport infrastructure construction.</seg>
<seg id="11">Audit institutions should not only highlight the shortcomings identified, but recommend measures to improve the situation, for the benefit of citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">The two supreme audit institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SRN and the Czech Republic) of the Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as the "BRH") and the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the "SAO") carried out parallel checks in 2005 and 2006 on expenditure on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (motorway D 8 v</seg>
<seg id="14">Motorways are connected by a border bridge co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to the cooperation with the SAO, the BRH was able to carry out a thorough check on the effectiveness of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">On the basis of close cooperation with BRH, the SAO obtained for comparative purposes the necessary data on the amount of German costs of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="17">The Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract for the construction of a border bridge in 2000.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the construction process, the completion date was finally scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the procurement process, the Directorate of Roads and Motorways of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "MSD") committed errors that led to the extension of the competition period and the shortening of the construction period.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was thus signed later than anticipated.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time and ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, however, MSD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint control work, the prices of bridges on motorways D 8 and A 17 were compared based on the conversion per m2 of the bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="24">The statistical analysis of prices made it possible to identify bridges with high costs per m2 of area.</seg>
<seg id="25">Analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in a group of large bridges over 100 meters long.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase could also be attributed to the delay in the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="27">When analysing the cost of building the tunnels, the inspectors found that the prices of tunnels on the D 8 motorway were significantly higher than those of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">The BRH and the SAO now have a database of bridge and tunnel prices that they will be able to rely on for future checks on the effectiveness of the funds used for transport infrastructure purposes.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, the two audit institutions recommend: the standardisation of bridge structures and the use of coupled steel-concrete and special structures only in cases where biased reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">Among the main features of the cooperation was its team spirit and informality.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel inspection, the auditors participated in their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report reports on the progress and results of parallel checks on funds spent on the construction of the motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The controls focused on the cost-effectiveness, efficiency and effectiveness of the expenditure incurred.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel checks were carried out by the BRH in Germany and the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel checks took place in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO audited the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure amounting to approximately CZK 20 billion including VAT (approximately €690 million) on the border section of the D 8 motorway, which has the number 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million of European funds (ISPA) was planned to be used.</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to the parallel checks carried out jointly with the SAO, BRH inspected the preparation and construction of motorway A 17 in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of motorway A 17 amounted to approximately € 670 million, of which € 277 million will be co-financed by the European Funds (EFRE).</seg>
<seg id="41">The motorway from Prague to Dresden is part of the trans-European transport corridor IV. Dresden - Central and Southern Eastern Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">Highway D 8 runs from Prague via Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">Motorway A 17 runs from the Czech Republic/Germany national border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">Border sections of both motorways were under construction at the time of inspection.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections were put into operation on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side, the motorway is finished up to Dresden, while on the Czech side the D 8 motorway is not finished, because section 0805, 16.4 km across the Czech Central Mountain between Řehlovice and Lovosice, is still in the preparatory phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, section 0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem is to pass through the protected landscape area of the Czech Central Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to the forecasts carried out in the Czech Republic in 2001, the traffic intensity of 22,940 vehicles per day should be on the border section No. 0807 of highway D 8 in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to German forecasts, in 2010 the traffic intensity at the Czech border will total about 25,000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, Germany and the Czech Republic concluded a Treaty between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic on the interconnection of the German motorway A 17 and the Czech highway D 8 at the common state border by building a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both States are involved in the construction of the bridge, so monitoring the construction of the bridge was an important aspect of the parallel checks carried out by the two audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and SAO</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid- 2005, the two highest audit institutions have discussed close cooperation in the control of the construction of the highway connecting Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both parties had serious reasons for such cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">GERMANY contributes financially to the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction is based on MSD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to inspect this construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have at its disposal the comparative database needed to assess whether the funds were used economically in terms of the overall level of costs for bridges and tunnels on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to ensure the effectiveness of expenditure, taking into account the main technical parameters of the motorway, in particular the arrangement of bridges and tunnels, which should allow the same quality of travel on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, the Agreement on Coordinated Highway Control D 8/A 17 was signed by the Presidents of the two Supreme Audit Institutions on 4 January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="64">Joint working meetings of the BRH and SAO auditors took place throughout 2006 at an interval of approximately six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">The negotiations dealt with current problems and tasks, in particular the preparation of a uniform methodology for controlling the prices of bridges and tunnels, the exchange of findings from border bridge inspections and the preparation of joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The ongoing exchange of information was an important feature of cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="67">While BRH carried out most of the work on the comparison of technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and procurement procedures, the SAO largely prepared a methodology for monitoring the prices of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="68">The applicable regulatory standards for control in government differ in the way control actions are concluded in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="69">For these reasons, the two Supreme Audit Institutions have drawn their own audit conclusions on their findings obtained during their checks.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report reflects the results achieved during the parallel checks.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation will end with the signing of the final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of a border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 Treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed on a deadline for completion of the border bridge construction as far as possible in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="74">The two parties then agreed to postpone this deadline until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">As an investor, MSD was active.</seg>
<seg id="76">GERMANY contributes financially to the construction of the bridge from 42.13%.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the period up to 1999, the MSD proposed that the border bridge should have a biased reinforced concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, in agreement with its partners in Germany, MSD agreed to a related steel-concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">This Decision was justified by the reduction of the number of double pillars from seven to five and the subsequent ecological benefit of such a solution to the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">Moreover, the comparative calculations carried out by MSD indicated that the coupled steel-concrete construction should be a less expensive option.</seg>
<seg id="81">But there was a mistake in the calculations.</seg>
<seg id="82">They indicated that the new coupled steel-concrete structure would be only 397 m long.</seg>
<seg id="83">It's actually 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award of the border bridge contract, the MSD made serious errors.</seg>
<seg id="85">It did not prepare the contract documentation to adequately describe the assessment criteria and sub-criteria for the benchmarking of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="86">This error led to a subjective and problematic evaluation by the Bid Assessment and Evaluation Board and the Director-General.</seg>
<seg id="87">The unsuccessful bidder contested the results of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">A subsequent investigation by the Competition Authority resulted in the contract for the award of the construction contract being signed later than originally envisaged.</seg>
<seg id="89">This meant that the 2004 summer construction season was wasted after the evaluation of the bids and that the construction period was reduced.</seg>
<seg id="90">The construction company agreed to build the bridge in a shorter period of time, but at the cost of a substantial increase in costs.</seg>
<seg id="91">The offered procedure included double mounting of the bridge superstructure, change in the construction of the pillars and establishment and equipment of the assembly premises.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the construction company was unable to obtain the originally designed type of steel at the necessary time.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel - at a cost of roughly €4 million, which had to be fully reimbursed by MSD - made it possible to shorten the period for the implementation of anti-corrosion protection, which in turn made it possible to reduce the total period of construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the net price of €18.3 million offered in the tender, the total cost of building the border bridge will increase considerably as a result of the accelerated procedure and other financing adjustments.</seg>
<seg id="95">The reduced period of time reserved for construction work led to an increase in the price of approximately €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">The net cost is currently around €25.9 million, without taking into account automatic price increases (as at October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of bridge and tunnel prices</seg>
<seg id="98">The two supreme audit institutions analysed the prices of bridges on motorways D 8 and A 17 in order to identify bridges whose price was too high and to compare the prices of bridges on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The analysis was based on methods of mathematical statistics.</seg>
<seg id="100">Furthermore, tunnels on D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on motorways in Germany (A 71, A 38 and A 4).</seg>
<seg id="101">There are no similar tunnels on Highway A 17.</seg>
<seg id="102">In preparing this part of the check, it was important to identify the relevant prices accurately.</seg>
<seg id="103">The two supreme audit institutions set the following principles for comparing the prices of bridges: to be based on the actual price paid for the bridge without value added tax (VAT rates vary in the Czech Republic and SNR and are subject to changes); not to take into account prices for special bridge bases; convert prices in CZK to € according to the European Central Bank rate applicable to 30.12.2005 (CZK 29 = €1).</seg>
<seg id="104">On D 8 i A 17 there are bridges of various structures (steel-concrete, biased reinforced concrete, coupled steel-concrete and steel) and various sizes.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure homogeneity of the structures examined, bridges were divided into groups according to the type of construction.</seg>
<seg id="106">Within these groups, the size of the bridge was also taken into account in the analyses.</seg>
<seg id="107">By far the most common type of construction on both sides of the border were concrete bridges (20 bridges on D 8, 36 bridges on A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The analysis focused primarily on this group of bridges, since the number of sets allowed the use of mathematical and statistical methods with a high degree of reliability of results.</seg>
<seg id="109">Checks found that the prices per m of 2 concrete bridges on D 8 i A 17 depend on the size of the bridge (its length, area): the larger the bridge, the lower the price per m2 of bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the price dependence was stronger than for Czech bridges (see graphs below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two concrete bridges were identified on A 17 and four on D 8, whose price is significantly higher.</seg>
<seg id="112">To find these bridges, a method was used to detect atypical values in a set of numbers, and a regression analysis taking into account the dependence of the bridge's price on its size (for determining atypically expensive bridges, the standard distance from the regression curve is upwards).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, information on the atypically high price of those bridges should only be considered as an indicator of which bridges need to be targeted.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw a generally applicable conclusion, the causes of the high price should be analysed in each identified case.</seg>
<seg id="115">One such cause may be inefficient administrative measures or environmental protection requirements or other acceptable grounds.</seg>
<seg id="116">Given that Czech concrete bridges are on average longer than German ones (see table below), the proven negative dependence of the bridge's price on its length could lead to the assumption that Czech bridges should be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">The hypothesis about lower prices of Czech concrete bridges is also supported by lower labour costs in the construction industry in the Czech Republic compared to the German Republic.</seg>
<seg id="118">However, the results of the analysis show that the prices of concrete bridges on D 8 are higher than on A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">During the joint negotiations, two possible causes of this situation were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, most bridges are awarded as separate contracts.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an award allows small and medium-sized regional firms to participate in the contract contest.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic many bridges are awarded as part of the contract for part of the motorway route, which is several kilometres long.</seg>
<seg id="124">Small and medium-sized companies do not participate in such a competition because the contract is too big for them.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic there is more variability in bridge construction than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the SAO found that the type of bridge construction is decided long before its construction.</seg>
<seg id="128">The decision shall be taken at the time when the MSD translates the request for a territorial decision.</seg>
<seg id="129">Although MSD selects types of bridges from several variants at this time, economics plays a smaller role in decision making.</seg>
<seg id="130">The general conclusion on the prices of bridges in the Czech Republic and Germany could only be made on the basis of a thorough analysis of the construction market in both countries, which would however go beyond this control action.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive coupled steel concrete bridge on D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of tunnels, the prices of tunnels on D 8 were found to be twice as high as those in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, the comparison of the main construction and technical parameters of the tunnels on D 8 with the tunnels in Germany showed no significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">Significant price differences could be attributed to the fact that there is no real competition in the Czech Republic in the field of tunnel construction.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, a small number of tunnels did not make it possible to draw generally applicable conclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Efficiency and efficiency of construction of the Dresden motorway - Prague</seg>
<seg id="137">A separate Czech Republic was established in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">The government approved the concept of the development of the motorway network in the same year.</seg>
<seg id="139">The D 8 motorway should be gradually extended from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section No. 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains should have been acquired earlier than the border section No. 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic acquires motorway D 8 within the framework of programme funding.</seg>
<seg id="142">The programme No. 327 220 "Construction of the motorway D 8 Prague - Ústí nad Labem - state border of the Czech Republic/Germany" set two objectives for the construction of the motorway D 8:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">improve the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem - a national objective;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">improve the links between Prague and Berlin in the framework of IV. the trans-European transport corridor Berlin - Istanbul - an international objective.</seg>
<seg id="147">According to the programme, construction of the section running through the Czech Central Mountains was to be completed in June 2008 and construction of the border section No. 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It must be added here that the completion date is not identical to the commissioning date.</seg>
<seg id="149">The SAO found that the preparation of the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Mountains is now at the stage of an official territorial decision.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental activists have challenged this decision with lawsuits.</seg>
<seg id="151">There is no final decision on the actions.</seg>
<seg id="152">Therefore, it cannot be excluded that the section running through the Czech Central Mountains will be completed several years later than mentioned in the programme documentation.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed to postpone the completion of section 0805 for 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result of these facts, the construction of the border section did not achieve the national objective - to improve the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The MSD made an estimate of capital expenditure on the border section D 8 No 0807 and section No 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains in 1999 - 2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The estimate in this capital expenditure of the included investment costs is about €639 million combined for both sections 0805 and 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Economic assessment results (EIRR = internal rate of return)</seg>
<seg id="158">All considered motorways and speed roads opened, both sections of D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
