<seg id="163">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 25 000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic analysis carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the border section and section through the Czech Central Mountains would be completed in time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of inspection, however, it is clear that the section through the Czech Central Mountains will not be open at the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This will reduce the above mentioned EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">The cost of both sections, excluding VAT, as at 31 December 2005, was €897 million, i.e. higher by 27.4% than the level of costs with which the 2001 economic analysis was carried out.</seg>
<seg id="168">However, there is a risk that section 0805 will be run on a different, more costly route, which would affect the aforementioned economic viability threshold.</seg>
<seg id="169">The economic analysis showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically viable with a traffic intensity of at least 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="170">The forecast for 2008 was 22,940 vehicles, but a study addressing the problem of roadside routes for the missing section across the Czech Central Mountains foresees a traffic intensity of 12,600 to 13,750 vehicles per day, pushing the investment below the economic viability threshold.</seg>
<seg id="171">In the case of higher loads of roadways for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains, there is a high probability of congestion and thus an increase in external costs, which were not foreseen in the original economic analysis.</seg>
<seg id="172">The above-mentioned decrease in revenues and cost increases means that the EIRR that the construction of the border section D 8 was to have had will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">Construction of the D 8 border section is therefore inefficient.</seg>
<seg id="174">Also during the construction of the A 17 motorway there was a similar excess of costs as in the case of these two sections on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment of the federal road development plan for long-distance transport for 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport of Germany envisaged a cost of about €320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">The resulting cost-benefit ratio was 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, however, costs have soared to about €670 million and the cost-benefit ratio has fallen by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">In addition to the parallel checks carried out jointly with the SAO, the BRH audited the preparation and construction of motorway A 17 in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="179">In doing so, the BRH found that the competent approval authority had requested an off-road tunnel for Section A 17, which was not needed.</seg>
<seg id="180">During the control operation, BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the German Administration for Road Construction that the tunnel was not necessary.</seg>
<seg id="181">This resulted in savings of around €10 million and €0.15 million in annual operating costs alone.</seg>
<seg id="182">When assessing the first section A 17, BRH found that the construction project was not properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">This is illustrated by the following example:</seg>
<seg id="184">At the preparatory stage, the Road Construction Administration did not survey the rock floor conditions in the Dölzschen rocks because the site was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">This was done only after the tunnel strike machine hit the rock.</seg>
<seg id="186">Tests showed that the rocks inside were more stale than anticipated during the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="187">Therefore, costly measures such as anchoring, injection and stone protection nets had to be taken, requiring around €3.3 million.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Directorate of Roads and Motorways had to bear the costs not only of other extraordinary operations, such as the safety measures in the Dölzschen rocks, but also of measures that would not have been needed if the construction project had been properly prepared first.</seg>
<seg id="189">Expenditure of this kind includes costs related to interruption of construction operations (€3.2 million), additional training of drilling staff (€0.5 million) and rising wages and expenditure on goods due to exceeding the duration of the project (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">The cost overruns thus amounted to around €10.7 million, which was not matched by any added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">On the basis of lessons learned from these and other controlled projects, BRH asked the Federal Ministry to apply stricter guidance in its supervision of road construction work.</seg>
<seg id="192">The Federal Ministry should give the Directorate of Roads and Motorways the necessary incentive to implement quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of cooperation for BRH and SAO Cooperation fulfilled the intention of both audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">BRH gained control knowledge about the preparation, commissioning and progress of the border bridge construction.</seg>
<seg id="195">The two Supreme Audit Institutions have built a database of bridges and tunnels prices on which to rely on future controls.</seg>
<seg id="196">The SAO found that the main building-technical parameters of bridges, tunnels and the route of the D 8 motorway are not different from the parameters of A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors of the two institutions involved in the cooperation have gained new experience which can be used for further inspections.</seg>
