<p>
<seg id="1">Public works procurement and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on parallel control carried out by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Public procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and the private sphere.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the State is to use public resources as efficiently and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor in the success of the single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">The EU has set limits in its rules, beyond which the contracting authority must meet certain requirements to guarantee a wide and unrestricted competitive environment across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts that are below EU value limits, regulation of their procurement remains the responsibility of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Moreover, public procurement is prone to corruption with a consequent high potential for harm.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting entities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and unfair favouritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI - SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI - BRH) agreed to carry out parallel checks on procurement procedures and the prevention of corruption in land and transport structures.</seg>
<seg id="14">Cooperation was also focused on European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The controls included the award of contracts below European thresholds in order to affect the area of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit findings of the two supreme audit institutions are summarised in a joint report, inter alia addressed to international organisations such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Control areas and controlled institutions</seg>
<seg id="18">The evaluation of BRH is based on the blanket checks of the above mentioned areas carried out by the German construction administrations responsible for federal transport and land construction between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, highway construction and large-scale building projects have been evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">The BRH also included findings from past inspections in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The SAO's evaluation is based on inspections carried out between 2008 and 2012, which focused on the construction of roads, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other buildings in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the award of federal public contracts is mostly carried out by regional construction administrations.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, public procurement in the field of transport infrastructure is the responsibility of the state institution for road and railway construction.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the field of civil engineering, public procurement is carried out by the beneficiaries of the budget.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used in the various stages of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation should take into account differences in public procurement legislation and the specificity of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of the Public Procurement Act in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the conduct of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and sub-legal standards.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany shall be governed by budgetary law and by the relevant administrative acts.</seg>
<seg id="30">The internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details concerning the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are enshrined in the so-called procurement manuals of the federal government, in which the requirements are developed or formulated in greater detail with regard to legal precedents in the field of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation concerning contracts with a value above and below European limits.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement law has undergone substantial changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules have strengthened transparency in procurement procedures, opened up room for greater competition and reduced opportunities for corruption in the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="35">Fundamental aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As regards European procurement procedures, open and restricted procedures must be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts under the European limit are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for competition, limited call for participation, negotiated procedure), but these are practically identical to the above mentioned conditions for European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates are invited on a European scale) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and in a call for competition, any candidate may submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized firms.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is mainly achieved by dividing the total public contract into commercial specific parts and dividing it into sub-contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">The award of contracts divided into these parts gives the opportunity to participate in the procedure as many candidates as possible.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German procurement law represent over time tested instruments for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330 000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are registered in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic it is necessary to apply the conditions of European procedures even in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">The exception is a simplified sub-standard procedure where the contracting authority may use less demanding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which a contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between open procedures and restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="49">85 000 construction companies are registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1 900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Total volume of contracting authorities' public works contracts and share of each type of procedure in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction work in Germany amounted to 7,675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">CZK, of which CZK 1,138 billion (15%) was the share of public contracts, which included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities in addition to those awarded by the Federal Government.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of projects of federal road and land structures (without construction of railways and water structures) reached CZK 212.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of federal land works and transport construction contracts was as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public calls; 12.7% narrower management and closer challenges;</seg>
<seg id="55">6,6% negotiated procedures and direct procurement; 33.2% is the share of European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic reached CZK 118.6 billion in 2011, which was about 25% of the total volume of construction work.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009 it amounted to CZK 194.0 billion, which was 37% of the total volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of procurement types in 2011: 65.1% open procedures; 14.3% restricted driving; 9,5% of the negotiated procedure; 8,4% simplified procedures for sub-prime contracts; 2,7% other proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="59">These data include all public supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">These figures show that: parallel checks in both countries focused on a substantial part of the public procurement procedures; the prevention of corruption, which must still be taken into account in procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open meaning. procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and the BRH carried out parallel checks on the award of European works contracts with an emphasis on preventing corruption in their countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The checks focused on the comparison of legislation in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public procurement in the field of land and transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">Key findings are also presented:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national rights of both countries (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">The prevention of corruption is not only the aim of the EU Directive, but the national procurement rules of both countries, which differ in part in terms of focus and detail.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the essential requirement to be met by the procurement documents is to include all the information necessary for the preparation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specifications shall be neutral and shall not contain any requirements limiting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">The procurement documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic the problem is the insufficient definition of the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, dividing contracts into parts where possible is required in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the findings of BRH, this requirement is respected in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">Audits of the SAO have shown that in the Czech Republic very large public works in the field of road construction are awarded without being divided into parts, or divided into parts, but only on very significant volumes. This can distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">These market potential constraints may result in significant cost increases and risk unserious price behaviour and inadmissible conventions.</seg>
<seg id="75">The legislation in both countries allows contracting entities, under certain conditions, to award additional works if the need arises only after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">The requirements for the correct identification of the type of procurement procedure are met in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, according to the applicable regulations, contracting entities may arbitrarily designate one of the open procurement procedures, namely an open procedure or a restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">The German rules on procurement and budgetary law give priority to open procedures for both European tenders and national tenders, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">Open procurement procedures in both countries allow a larger range of candidates to submit a tender and also reduce the risk of corruption by making it difficult to negotiate prices illegally between candidates.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best results are achieved in terms of value for money.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts whose estimated total price is above or above the EU thresholds, the audited contracting entities have always issued a European procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="82">Proper determination of the estimated value of the contract plays a very important role in determining the type of procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used for objective pricing of public works in which values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective tool.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the field of road construction, but they are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a works contract under European procurement procedures, it is necessary to publish the preliminary information and the notice of initiation in order to strengthen competition by allowing candidates to prepare in time for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction authorities audited complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and/or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">When selecting candidates to participate in a restricted procurement procedure, there is a greater risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be sufficiently high to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria shall be objective, non-discriminatory and shall be published sufficiently in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to EU requirements, contracting authorities in both countries should alternate as frequently as possible the candidates who are invited to participate in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany there are some very detailed requirements for preventing the risks of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited contracting entities did not comply with these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (section 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting authorities must ensure during the procurement procedure that all candidates wishing to submit a tender receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between those interested parties and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications must be prevented to the extent possible from limiting competition in the form of illegal agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the audited German contracting authorities did not meet the above requirement in several cases (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">Labelling, documentation, protection and confidentiality requirements are designed to limit the scope for handling and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">Inspections in both countries identified only a few cases of irregularities (section 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The assessment and evaluation of tenders is procedurally regulated in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more comprehensive but have not always been respected by the audited contracting entities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting entities transmitted their tenders to third parties for consultation without prior assessment, without properly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">The tenders were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulations (point 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">The intended award of the contract must be subject to legal protection of enterprises are to be informed about the intended contract award before the latter is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection rule is also designed to prevent corruptive action.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of contract award procedures also for national tenders.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the notification of the enterprises was not appropriately ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The tender documentation for the audited contracting entities in both countries was not always complete or fully credible.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, transparency requirements applied at European level have not always been adequately complied with in the minutes of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="113">In addition, some of the deficiencies identified reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the dossier.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting entities in both countries mostly fulfilled their reporting obligations (point 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of the guiding principles of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">European procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">The European Parliament and the Council of the European Union have adopted, inter alia, a directive on the coordination of public works procurement procedures to ensure free competition in the EU, supplies and services to ensure the free movement of goods and services and the Directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to review procedures for the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (Review Procedures Directive), the two Directives being transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general procurement principles of the EU include in particular: the requirement for a competitive environment; a requirement for equal treatment or non-discrimination; a requirement for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">in addition, the EU procurement principles include the Directive on the coordination of procurement procedures includes provisions relating to construction projects whose total expected value is or exceeds €5 million.</seg>
<seg id="120">These provisions affect: the contents of the procurement documents; the type of procurement procedure used; the publication of certain information before, during and after the completion of the procedure; compliance with the deadline for receipt of tenders; qualification requirements which may be required of candidates; criteria for selecting the most appropriate tender.</seg>
<seg id="121">Legal protection of tenderers is governed by the Review Procedures Directive.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of a potential breach of the procurement law, tenderers may have the decision of the contracting authority reviewed in accordance with the examination procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both countries have transposed EU requirements into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">The importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">In either country, there is no legal definition of what corruption actually means.</seg>
<seg id="127">Corruption is generally seen as an abuse of a personal (confidential) position for its own benefit.</seg>
<seg id="128">As a rule, this means that such abuse is prompted by the beneficiaries.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hinder competition and cause serious economic losses.</seg>
<seg id="130">Overall corruption-related damage is estimated to account for 5% of world economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the EU, these costs are estimated at 1% of the EU's economic output.</seg>
<seg id="132">Where a contracting authority is involved in the contract, conventions limiting competition or allowing dishonest conduct may undermine confidence in the integrity, capacity and overall work of the public administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Therefore, prevention of corruption is an essential task for contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">Practice and practices must be monitored in particular in areas particularly vulnerable to corruption in order to take adequate measures to prevent it.</seg>
<seg id="135">The adoption of preventive measures and the implementation of effective controls can significantly reduce the susceptibility of the decision-making process to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="136">The award of works contracts is generally regarded as particularly vulnerable to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures to prevent corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption is prosecutable under criminal and labour law, which is particularly relevant to active and passive bribery, the reception and offering of significant benefits.</seg>
<seg id="139">The German Federal Government issued a manual with recommendations on the prevention of corruption in the Federal Administration and according to which the following principles are applied throughout the entire procurement process beyond risk analysis: the preference for open procurement; the principle of multiple control and transparent decision-making; separation of planning, procurement and accounting phases; accurate and complete documentation of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, other measures preventing corruption have become part of the procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, the relevant Federal Ministry of Information Technology introduced a system for monitoring procurement for the construction of federal roads.</seg>
<seg id="142">With this system, data such as estimated costs, the total value of the contract and the involvement of private projection offices can be fully recorded and analysed in order to identify any irregularities.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is prosecuted under criminal law, and a level of labour or civil law is also considered.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirement for transparency, equal treatment and prohibition of any discrimination throughout the procurement process (preparation and implementation) is the most important part of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">Anti-corruption measures in this area were set out by the Government in the "Government Strategy against Corruption 2011 to 2012," updated for 2013 and 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Part of these measures has been incorporated into the Act on Public Procurement and Successive Implementing Regulations.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation contains the following basic provisions: lowering the thresholds for small-scale contracts; the obligation to notify the contracting authority ex ante, including the reasons for the contract; a prohibition on limiting the number of shortlisted tenderers and abolishing the general possibility of limiting the number of applicants by drawing lots; the obligation to publish contracts, including annexes; the obligation to publish actual and lists of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Results of the checks relating to the subsequent stages of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Procurement documents</seg>
<seg id="150">The tender documents shall contain all the information necessary to enable tenderers to prepare their tenders in an appropriate form.</seg>
<seg id="151">The documentation shall in particular enable the tender price to be processed.</seg>
<seg id="152">In order to do so, candidates must not be exposed to risks which they could not reckon with.</seg>
<seg id="153">The tender documents contain specifications in particular, as well as requirements for proving the qualifications of tenderers and criteria for the selection of the most advantageous tender.</seg>
<seg id="154">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="155">In particular, European law contains requirements relating to technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="156">The specifications must minimise competition and all interested parties must have equal access to them.</seg>
<seg id="157">The specification must be neutral.</seg>
<seg id="158">Requirements for specific products are permitted on a very limited scale in the procurement documents.</seg>
<seg id="159">The basic principle of corruption prevention is that the procurement documents do not contain requirements that might restrict competition.</seg>
<seg id="160">Furthermore, the documentation should avoid confusion or inaccurate data that create room for speculation and manipulation in the evaluation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="161">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="162">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="163">Both countries have transposed EU legal provisions into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="164">The basic principle is that specifications are generally given without reference to a particular product or brand.</seg>
<seg id="165">Specifications shall specify the required supplies and services and specify in detail the number of units of work and supply.</seg>
<seg id="166">In normal cases, prices should be indicated by units of works or supplies (e.g. in CZK/m or in CZK/item).</seg>
<seg id="167">Defining the work required in terms of its functionality is only permissible in exceptional cases.</seg>
<seg id="168">In principle, the rule is that specifications need to be drawn up completely and unambiguously.</seg>
<seg id="169">They shall contain precise quantities and shall not include works and supplies the necessity of which is not entirely obvious.</seg>
<seg id="170">Payment in the form of lump sums or according to the time worked should be avoided wherever possible.</seg>
<seg id="171">These parts of the procurement documents shall exclude speculation and manipulation based on ambiguous specifications.</seg>
<seg id="172">The specifications must allow each tenderer to prepare his offer with certainty and without excessive preparatory work.</seg>
<seg id="173">The invitation to tender shall not be published until the procurement documents are complete.</seg>
<seg id="174">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="175">In the Czech Republic there is no obligation for contracting entities to award construction contracts in parts.</seg>
<seg id="176">The contracting authority may divide the contract into several separate parts, provided that the nature of the subject-matter of such a contract so permits.</seg>
<seg id="177">Germany requires the application of the rule to divide works into parts, either quantitatively (partial supplies) or according to specific aspects (specialised parts of the contract).</seg>
<seg id="178">This enables small and medium-sized entities to participate in the competition, increases the number of potential bidders and makes price fixation difficult.</seg>
<seg id="179">This type of award is usually considered most appropriate in terms of providing value for money.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, procurement documents must contain evaluation criteria for national and European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="181">This should inform the tenderer in a comprehensive and exhaustive manner of the criteria on which the tender will be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="182">In Germany, the requirement to include evaluation criteria in the notification applies only to European calls for tenders.</seg>
<seg id="183">In national procurement procedures, evaluation criteria must only be included in the contract record, which is an internal administrative document.</seg>
<seg id="184">If the procurement documents are prepared by authorized independent experts, German regulations require the exclusion of any information that would help identify specific interested companies, architects or designers.</seg>
<seg id="185">The reason is to prevent individual construction companies from obtaining any additional information or other unacceptable competitive advantages without the knowledge of the contracting authority through contacts with these independent experts.</seg>
<seg id="186">This is also why independent experts are not allowed to publish tender documents and make them accessible for screening.</seg>
<seg id="187">The contracting authority is the only contact point for construction companies.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Czech Republic does not currently have a similar provision.</seg>
<seg id="189">In the case of large construction projects, after the conclusion of the original contract, there will almost always be a need for additional work or modification of existing works.</seg>
<seg id="190">The legislation of both countries makes it possible to award a multi-work contract within a certain limit to the same supplier without the need to publish and implement a new procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="191">The volume of multipliers under European and German legislation must not exceed 50% of the original value of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="192">Moreover, multi-machinery must be necessary and have the character of a specific component of the main contract.</seg>
<seg id="193">In the Czech Republic, a stricter limit of 20% is applied for the award of multipliers.</seg>
<seg id="194">This may lead to a risk of a greater time lag in the execution of the contract and the possible integration of a new entity into an already running project.</seg>
<seg id="195">Where a multi-work contract is awarded to the supplier of the original contract, German law contains a provision preventing suppliers from arbitrarily increasing the price of modified works or multipliers.</seg>
<seg id="196">Calculations shall be made taking into account the prices agreed in the original contract.</seg>
<seg id="197">In addition to multipliers, there may be minor works during construction, i.e. works that were not needed.</seg>
<seg id="198">In the Czech Republic it is not possible to compensate for each other.</seg>
<seg id="199">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="200">BHR</seg>
<seg id="201">Technical specifications and product neutral invitation to tender</seg>
