<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and confirms the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the correctness of the application of the procurement law reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting entity will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by swiftly implementing the procurement decision.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority shall document the procedure accordingly.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries have implemented information obligations for management.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, it cannot arbitrarily deviate from the results of a properly conducted review and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority shall conclude the contract within a specified period of time.</seg>
<seg id="723">The reason is that the tenderer is not bound by his bid after the expiry of this deadline.</seg>
<seg id="724">The contents of the contract shall not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">The unsuccessful tenderers should be informed of the result in good time, stating why their bid was not accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">Cancellation of the procurement procedure is only permissible if certain conditions are met, e.g. if the prices in the tenders do not conform to the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory pre-contract waiting period of 10 or 15 days applies to both European and national proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, equivalent provisions apply only to European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of the contract before deciding on its EU provisions and the review award.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure must be cancelled if a single tender has been received or only one tender meets the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, a contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender meets the conditions laid down in the procurement documents and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">Few irregularities were found in the completion of controlled procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases, European procedures have been granted to letter companies prior to the expiry of the notification period, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also, in several open procedures, the authorising letters contained modifications incompatible with the contents of the tender, e.g. new time limits.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting authorities have failed to meet the award deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous tender because the tenderer offering a price more than 50% lower no longer wished to fulfil the contract at the price originally offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">SAO</seg>
<seg id="741">During the reconstruction and construction of the university, the contracting authority did not conclude a contract with the contractor in accordance with the draft contract contained in the tender of the selected tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some road repair and maintenance operations, the construction of the motorway and the road circuit, contracts were concluded later than laid down by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">In the case of construction modifications in former military injuries, the contracting authority has sent a notice of the selection of the most suitable tender to all tenderers only after the expiry of the legal period.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented EU rules on the closure of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="746">Legal protection of unsuccessful candidates contributes to reducing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act includes an institute of legal protection even in cases of contracts below EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that the limited contract time limit was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting authorities should eliminate such shortcomings when concluding the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notifications, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process with all its individual stages, relevant findings and decisions, including the relevant justifications, shall be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">The completion of the procurement procedure at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">Data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of European law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document the procurement procedure is in line with the basic requirement of the principle of transparency, applied at EU-wide level.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only sound and timely documentation on decision-making and rationale guarantees transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each tenderer in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European limits.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to give detailed reasons for individual decisions and their justification significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In the case of European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify their completion to the EU Publications Office of Official Publications within 48 days of the award date.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU and the transparency requirement is fulfilled.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the relevant information on its procurement procedures and communicate it to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission publishes annual statistics to provide an overview of the development of the single market in construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed the provisions of the European Law on Documentation and Notification Obligations into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for the purposes of European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify a contract does not only apply to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notification period is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those compulsory under European law, applies only to restricted procedures exceeding the threshold of EUR 25 000 (CZK 625 000) and direct procedures exceeding the threshold of EUR 15 000 (CZK 375 000), including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Only parties shall be informed below this limit.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of entries have not been fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notification did not contain all the necessary information, e.g. reasons for supply specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of one procedure, the contracting authority has not explained why it entered into a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain mandatory formalities.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some of the required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="780">In the case of certain European procedures, the contracting authority erred in publishing the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of several entries, there was no evidence of publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="782">Notification obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">The scanned files included the minimum information required and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Pre-transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information on the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting entity, contract information was not disclosed due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the procurer six months to notice the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">Consequently, the outcome of the proceedings was not published during that period.</seg>
<seg id="789">SAO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">For events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, considerable weaknesses were identified in the documentation of the procurement process, such as incorrect data on bid prices in the evaluation committee's meeting protocols.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some documents about opening envelopes have not been signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of the award of the contract</seg>
<seg id="794">In the preparation of road repair and maintenance, construction of the motorway and road circuit, contract notices were sent after the deadline or were not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations cover European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">Czech reporting obligations are somewhat stricter compared to German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The checks revealed deficiencies significantly reducing the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">IRING segmentISintent  EU blank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to strengthen the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with the notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">Parallel controls of the SAO and BRH focused on two areas that are essential for the procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation provides an opportunity for international competition within the EU to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Measures aimed at preventing corruption are not merely aimed at avoiding or at least reducing corruption, but at the same time at preventing financial damage and possible loss of confidence in government integrity.</seg>
<seg id="806">The findings of the two audit institutions - the SAO and the BRH - with regard to the application of the procurement law of the two countries and the comparison of their respective provisions give an internal view of the common and different elements that can assist both countries in the further development and application of this law.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed EU public procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">In both countries there is thus an important common basis for public procurement and for meeting the essential requirements in the field of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting authorities reinforce these requirements partly through very extensive measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has laid down provisions on public procurement requiring European procedures and procedures that are below the EU limits and is therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, checks have shown that contracting entities are not always fully compliant with all relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate these irregularities taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, controls identified risks affecting the economy and achieving value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">It is in particular an incomplete definition of the subject matter of the contract, which resulted in additional work, which was often awarded in violation of the law, insufficient definition of the expected price and the required qualification assumptions narrowing the possible range of tenderers and thus reducing competition in particular in the field of transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">Joint controls were not intended to detect cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that both the BRH and the SAO did not have the tools to do so.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can check whether the competent authorities of both countries are taking measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">As regards the prevention of corruption, the two countries focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German provisions provide for wide and unrestricted competition, transparency and control as a central element in preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">In particular, Czech regulations aim to strengthen transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply to the entire federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles have also been included in public procurement requirements and have been adopted to meet the specific needs of such procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, occasionally and very precisely, ways of meeting the requirements for the prevention of corruption during the procurement procedure and of selecting the persons included therein.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the view of the BRH, the principle of preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly appropriate tool for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in public procurement, while limiting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate controls (in particular the cross-checking principle), transparency requirements, procurement documentation and various organisational measures are also effective mechanisms to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">Therefore, BRH does not feel the need to substantially amend the current provisions that public institutions must comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas highlighted weaknesses in compliance with certain requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting entities should provide further training to their employees, thereby enriching them with anti-corruption requirements and further raising their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the identified weaknesses refers to activities delegated by the construction administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the lack of adequate controls in delegating powers increases the risk of their abuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Therefore, activities susceptible to manipulation and corruption should only be transferred to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorised interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">SAO</seg>
<seg id="837">In the Czech Republic, anti-corruption strategies have been adopted at government level, which significantly affect the field of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">Audits of the SAO took place during the period when one of the most important parts of this strategy was implemented, namely a significant change of the Act on Public Procurement and the adoption of successive implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The strategy adopted and the new legislation can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">Under the new rules, for example, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the contract, the determination of the estimated value of the contract, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the establishment of the basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluation of tenders, and properly document and publish everything.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, both the SAO and the BRH have a favourable opinion on how to implement EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their broad application has confirmed in practice that EU competition, equal treatment and transparency requirements form an appropriate basis for EU public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="844">The transnational model, introduced in the EU, can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the large potential for material and intangible damage resulting from manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, both the BRH and the SAO insist that it is the obligation of the contracting authorities to continue measures against corruption and manipulation and to improve them where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organisational structures and procurement processes should be continuously monitored in terms of weaknesses and risks in order to identify and respond appropriately to the need for correction.</seg>
<seg id="847">In comparison with the practice in Germany, it appeared that the share of open procurement procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, giving room for competition and substantially reducing the possibility of corrupt behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="848">In cases where this is permissible and appropriate for contracting entities, partial procurement may also have a positive impact on the price achieved. The higher number of applicants puts pressure on the price achieved.</seg>
<seg id="849">The organisation of the procurement procedure is also affected.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is provided by special state organizations, whereas in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport constructions, it is organized by central authorities themselves or through contractual organizations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and the BRH wish to further develop knowledge in their work where appropriate and to address it with their parliament and government, beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they are convinced that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions. (INTOSAI), because these principles and findings are of general importance for the effective fight against corruption and for the guarantee that public contracts are awarded in a regime of well-functioning and fair competition and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Attachments</seg>
</p>
