<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_15_33" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="ref">
<p>
<seg id="1">JOINT FINAL REPORT ON THE RESULTS OF PARALLEL CONTROLS OF EXCISE ADMINISTRATION IN SR AND THE CZECH REPUBLIC</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint final report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="7">The submitted joint report informs on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, focusing on the administration of excise duties in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">Cooperation between the supreme audit institutions of both countries was implemented on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the SAO SR and the SAO of the Czech Republic in the performance of parallel controls aimed at the administration of excise taxes, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The theme of parallel controls was selected on the basis of the fact that the two EU Member States are based on common European legislation in order to determine how it is applied at national level, how the system of excise tax administration is set up and how the systems in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic differ.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the control actions was the exchange of experience, the identification of differences and the identification of good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Finally, it was beneficial to find that the international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise tax management is very limited without the implementation of parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrík,</seg>
<seg id="14">President</seg>
<seg id="15">Chairman</seg>
<seg id="16">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">on the results of parallel inspections of SPD management in SR and CR</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legislation of excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia and their administration is in accordance with EU law and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences were found between the excise tax treatment in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic. In the Czech Republic, the verification of the economic stability of applicants for authorisation and the compulsory marking and colouring of selected mineral oils and certain other oils contributes to the effective administration of excise taxes; In SR, the distribution of control stamps is easier than in the Czech Republic and less burdensome to the tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against excise evasion, supervision of the movement of raw tobacco or tobacco raw materials, implementation of the Institute of the Fuel Distributor and registration of retailers of consumer packaging of alcohol proved to be good practice in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="23">Excise revenue in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic is growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU's objectives of reducing labour taxation, introducing environmental austerity measures and reducing dependence on tobacco and alcohol have not yet been met in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, including because there is no indexation of excise duty rates in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This has the effect of reducing the importance of excise duties on total tax revenues and, as a result of increasing purchasing power, of reducing the tax burden on excise duties in real terms.</seg>
<seg id="26">The State has supported the implementation of environmental measures in the long term, but these measures have a negative impact on excise revenue, which will therefore need to be replaced in the future by other revenues or reductions in State expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenditure incurred in the administration of excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia has been increasing in the long term, mainly due to wage growth, and their efficiency is decreasing.</seg>
<seg id="28">In SR, this efficiency is also negatively affected by expenditure on electronisation of excise tax administration (IT expenditure) and expenses incurred on the wages of employees carrying out permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses for alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="29">The electronisation of excise tax administration in SR did not materially reflect the reduction in the number of tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO SR recommend that FŘ SR reconsider the merits of the exercise of permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses for alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the effectiveness of administrative expenditure was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures during the audited period that would reduce the staffing requirements of excise tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative acts of the tax administrators was similar in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in individual years of the audited period, while the number of comparable tax entities is about a third lower in the Slovak Republic than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in the Slovak Republic perform administrative tasks mainly in the form of physical exercise of tax supervision, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic place emphasis on remote supervision and risk analysis.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of excise taxes in the Slovak Republic is administratively more demanding than in the Czech Republic and, due to the ratio of the number of tax acts to the number of entities, more costly.</seg>
<seg id="35">Electronisation of excise tax administration in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic took place in different areas.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the Slovak Republic, the administration of excise tax returns is fully electronized; in the Czech Republic, documents proving the taxation of selected products in free tax circulation are transmitted electronically.</seg>
<seg id="37">Both methods of electronization support effective administration of excise taxes, which is why the SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO SR recommend applying them not only in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="38">The total expenditure for the implementation of the EMCS could not be compared as FŘ SR provided expenditure data only for the upgrade of the system in 2011-2015, but the expenditure was also spent before that period.</seg>
<seg id="39">Expenses incurred during that period only for the EMCS upgrade were approximately 20% higher in the Slovak Republic than those incurred in the Czech Republic for both the EMCS and the system upgrade over more than a decade.</seg>
<seg id="40">Excise administrators in the Czech Republic and Slovakia did not achieve comparable values of qualitative indicators when incurring comparable expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="41">The level of supervision is comparable in both countries, but in the Slovak Republic the management of excise duties is significantly more resource intensive.</seg>
<seg id="42">The introduction of the Electronic System for Monitoring the Movement of Excise Products (EMCS) has made the administration of excise duties more efficient, but in the Slovak Republic to a lower extent, as significantly higher expenditure was incurred on the introduction and modernisation of the system than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="43">Basic information</seg>
<seg id="44">Cooperation between the two audit institutions was carried out on the basis of the Cooperation Treaty in the implementation of parallel controls aimed at the management of excise duties of 18.8.2015.</seg>
<seg id="45">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO SR agreed to carry out parallel checks, which will be primarily focused on the issue of excise tax administration and the results of which will allow analysis, comparison and evaluation of the findings.</seg>
<seg id="46">Common audit issues were agreed on which parallel checks were based.</seg>
<seg id="47">Characteristics of subject matter and objectives of parallel control:</seg>
<seg id="48">The aim of the parallel controls was to compare the performance of excise administrators taking into account qualitative and quantitative indicators and to identify weaknesses in the excise management process.</seg>
<seg id="49">In particular, the following main audit questions should be answered:</seg>
<seg id="50">Were excise administrators in the Czech Republic and Slovakia achieving comparable values of qualitative indicators when incurring comparable expenditure?</seg>
<seg id="51">Has the introduction of the Excise Movement and Control System (EMCS) system made excise duty management more efficient and has the implementation expenses efficiently incurred?</seg>
<seg id="52">The parallel checks should have identified the causes of significant differences affecting the efficiency and effectiveness of the tax administration in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, especially in the area of legislation and in setting up the organisational structure.</seg>
<seg id="53">IRING segmentISintent  EU blank</seg>
<seg id="54">Directorate-General of Customs (GŘC) and Financial Directorate of SR (FD SR) have joined the Joint Declaration on mutual cooperation between the Visegrad Four countries, the objectives of this declaration include, inter alia, combating fraud, exploring the possibility of harmonising legislation and seeking harmonised interpretations on the rules of selected problems, exploring the possibility of joint activities to increase efficiency in detecting fraud and sharing experience and best practice.</seg>
<seg id="55">1 The EMCS is operated under Decision No 1152/2003/ES of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 establishing an electronic system for the transport and monitoring of excise products.</seg>
<seg id="56">Identification of the audit carried out by the SAO of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="57">Control number: 15/33</seg>
<seg id="58">Subject of inspection: Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="59">Objective of the inspection: The aim of the SAO of the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the customs authorities in the administration of excise duties, in particular when monitoring transport in the system of conditional exemption from excise duties and when securing tax (customs debts); verify that the excise management system is set up to ensure the efficiency of the collection of revenue of the state budget.</seg>
<seg id="60">Audited period: 2012-2015 and, in the case of factual contexts, the period preceding and subsequent</seg>
<seg id="61">Audited person: Directorate-General of Customs</seg>
<seg id="62">Identification of the audit carried out by the SAO SR</seg>
<seg id="63">Control number: KA-023/2016/1050</seg>
<seg id="64">Subject of inspection: Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="65">Objective of the inspection: The aim of the inspection was an independent and objective examination of whether the FŘ SR and the customs authorities (CA) operate economically, efficiently and effectively in the administration of excise duties in accordance with generally binding legislation.</seg>
<seg id="66">Audited period: 2012-2015</seg>
<seg id="67">Audited person: Financial Directorate of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="68">Legislation for excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="69">Excise legislation is divided into EU legislation (see Annex 1) and national legislation (see Annex 2).</seg>
<seg id="70">Council Directive 2008/118/ES, on the general arrangements for excise duties and repealing Directive 92/12/EHS, defines excise duty and defines the basic rules for the administration and management of energy products and electricity, tobacco products, alcohol and alcoholic beverages.</seg>
<seg id="71">This Directive allows for the imposition of consumption taxes on other products.</seg>
<seg id="72">In particular, EU legislation provides for minimum conditions for: the level of tax rates for the different types of products selected, the production, storage, processing and holding of taxable products, the taxation, exemption and refund, supervision of transport of selected products between EU Member States, international cooperation and the keeping of registers on economic operators and tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="73">EU legislation allows control procedures and institutes to be implemented at national level, provided they do not distort competition.</seg>
<seg id="74">Excise legislation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="75">Definition of legislation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="76">In the Czech Republic, excise legislation is concentrated in the Excise Tax Act (Act No. 353/2003 Coll.), which regulates the administration of mineral oil taxes, alcohol taxes, taxes on tobacco products, beer taxes, taxes on wine and intermediate products and taxes on raw tobacco.</seg>
<seg id="77">This Act defines the forms of handling of excise products, taxpayers, authorisation procedures, conditions for the transport of products, tax returns and penalties for infringements.</seg>
<seg id="78">The Act and subsequent Decrees further regulate certain other conditions for the management of mineral oils (branding of mineral oils), restrictions on the sale of spirits and tobacco products, monitoring of the handling of special mineral oils and storage of raw tobacco for purposes other than the manufacture of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="79">Taxes on other energy products (i.e. natural gas and certain other gases, solid fuels and electricity) are regulated in parts 45 to 47 of Act No. 261/2007 Coll., on the stabilization of public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="80">In the Czech Republic, a number of provisions related to the administration of excise duties are contained in special legislation. Act No. 311/2006 Coll. and the implementing regulation regulates the conditions for the sale, supply, distribution of fuel and the keeping of records of fuel put into free circulation.</seg>
<seg id="81">Act No. 61/1997 Coll., on alcohol, and its implementing regulations define the conditions for the production, storage, registration and control of the production and circulation of alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="82">Act No. 307/2013 Coll., on the compulsory labelling of alcohol, and the relevant implementing provisions provide for compulsory labelling of alcohol in consumer packaging, conditions for the handling of control tapes and conditions for the handling of alcohol (i.e. for the production, processing, sale or other transfer, transport, transport, storage, taking over, use, possession, import or export of alcohol).</seg>
<seg id="83">Tax procedures not specified in special regulations are governed by Act No. 280/2009 Coll., Tax Code.</seg>
<seg id="84">Penalties are imposed by procedures under Act No. 500/2004 Coll., Administrative Regulations.</seg>
<seg id="85">The conditions for issuing a trade licence (concession) for the operation of the trade "production and processing of fuels and lubricants and distribution of fuels" and "production, preparation and sale of yeast alcohol, spirit and spirits" are regulated by Act No. 455/1991 Coll., on the Business Enterprise (Trade Act).</seg>
<seg id="86">The Czech Republic has used the authorization to introduce control procedures and institutes for controlling the transport of selected products in free tax circulation and to supervise compliance with legislation in the handling of selected products for which no excise duty has been paid, as well as in the handling of selected products for which the tax has already been paid.</seg>
<seg id="87">These include monitoring the handling of specific mineral oils and raw tobacco, labelling of certain other mineral oils, labelling of tobacco products and alcohol in consumer packaging.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Czech Republic used the right to apply excise duty to other products and introduced excise duty on raw tobacco as one of the measures against tax fraud.</seg>
