<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel control of the administration of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The 1977 Lima Declaration stresses that Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) have the power to audit all public financing operations.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Declaration calls for tax revenues to be controlled to the greatest extent possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">It considers the European Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) to be one of the most important components of public tax revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">VI. the EUROSAI Congress held in Bonn in 2005 dealt with the audit of public revenues carried out by the SAI.</seg>
<seg id="7">An important step towards optimising the control activities of the SAI is the development of a specific strategy for auditing public revenues.</seg>
<seg id="8">This concerns, in particular, taxes as the most subtle source of public revenue, which is most susceptible to large losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and dependent, SAIs may, to a certain extent, be unable to carry out control activities without cooperation with another State's SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is the audit of internationally organised fraud, which causes substantial losses in the income of many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">To combat this crime, the responsible authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">SAIs carrying out checks in this area must be willing to establish closer cooperation with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">Right on VI. the EUROSAI Congress in Bonn has developed the idea of controlling the administration of value added tax (VAT) and the VIES system in the framework of cooperation between the Supreme Audit Office and the Federal Court of Auditors, the Bundesrechnungshof.</seg>
<seg id="14">This was followed by careful preparation, where both parties first had to familiarize themselves with the legal environment and procedures for the administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">On the basis of an analysis of this information, a selection was made of the control topics included in the control programme.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving effective and efficient VAT management is a long-term problem and individual countries (in particular the Member States of the European Union) are looking for solutions to improve, simplify and make the collection of this tax more transparent.</seg>
<seg id="17">We believe that the results of our control can serve not only to improve the work of tax administrators, but also as a basis for a proposal to improve the system of international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel checks on the administration of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Control number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject of inspection:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Administration of value added tax after the Czech Republic joins the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Control objective:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the audit action in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the administration of value added tax after the integration of the Czech Republic into the Single Internal Market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as "the EU") linked to the free movement of goods and services and to verify the use of the VIES system, in particular when checking the application of the right to value added tax exemption for intracommunitary supplies.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of control of intra-Community value added tax with a particular focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax under the aforementioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">The result should be a report on weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">System of exchange of information on value added tax Audits were carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (SAO) and the German Bundesrechnungshof (BRH) in mutual cooperation on the basis of a contract concluded between the two audit institutions on 8 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused mainly on the examination of selected business transactions between payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic") and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as "Germany"), the use of information obtained through international cooperation between tax administrations and comparison of VAT management systems of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">The joint final report on the results of the audit actions was prepared within the meaning of European Directive No 31 for the implementation of the audit standards of INTOSAI.</seg>
<seg id="31">The controlled period was the period from 1.5.2004 to 31.12.2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel control in the field of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of a contract between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="34">Outside the main point - information exchanges based on Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004 - control covered other topics, such as the registration of payers, VAT returns and summary reports, which are closely linked to the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">Moreover, the check included the legal situation in the area of international bus transport of passengers and the comparison of some statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">A comparison of the VAT management systems of the two countries identified differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the primary criterion (among other things) for registration is the exceedance of the limit laid down in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, only one tax identification number is allocated to payers, which they also use in intracommunity transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany a tax number is allocated to the payers at the time of registration for VAT, which is used only for commercial transactions in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If the German payer intracommunitary transactions intend to take place, he must request the assignment of a special identification number, VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">As different marketing authorisations cause problems, conditions should be settled across the EU (see. 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International bus transport of persons.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the Czech Republic, international bus transport of persons is exempt from VAT with a right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="45">In Germany, the part of the transport carried out on German territory is subject to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="46">Efforts should be made at EU level to harmonise the situation within the meaning of Article 393 of the Council Directive on the common system of VAT (see. 4.2)</seg>
<seg id="47">3) VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="48">While in the Czech Republic the payers submit VAT returns only for individual tax periods (month or quarter), in Germany the payers are obliged to submit so-called preliminary VAT returns (monthly or quarterly) and after the end of the calendar year they have to submit an annual VAT tax return.</seg>
<seg id="49">Unlike the Czech Republic, payers in Germany are obliged to submit preliminary tax returns electronically.</seg>
<seg id="50">The introduction of the obligation to submit tax returns for VAT in the Czech Republic electronically would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see. 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="51">4) Summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="52">While in the Czech Republic payers submit summary reports to the tax authorities, in Germany the payers submit summary reports to the Customs Office.</seg>
<seg id="53">The tax authorities in the Czech Republic therefore have data from the summary reports immediately after their submission.</seg>
<seg id="54">The information from the summary reports is only available to the German tax authorities after their processing into Customs.</seg>
<seg id="55">Combating VAT fraud requires that updated information on intracommunity transactions be made available as soon as possible.</seg>
<seg id="56">The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the time shift between the date of the transaction and the update of the data in the VIES.</seg>
<seg id="57">This would subsequently allow timely verification of taxation in the purchaser's Member State (see. 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="58">This would, however, require all Member States to adopt the same deadline for the submission of a summary report.</seg>
<seg id="59">5) International exchange of information in the field of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="60">The Czech Customs Office monitors compliance with the three-month deadline for received requests for information.</seg>
<seg id="61">The German Customs Office does not monitor the passage of time.</seg>
<seg id="62">Consequently, the German tax administration handled a significantly lower percentage of the applications received within the time limit.</seg>
<seg id="63">Because of these problems, BRH recommended that the German CLO carry out a permanent alert (see. 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="64">6) Risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="65">Each Member State develops its own risk management system (RMS), which has both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="66">The SAO and the BRH point out that effective RMS cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="67">Successful RMS criteria, components and approaches must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State, otherwise fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5th).</seg>
<seg id="68">Within the cooperation, both SAIs examined selected cases of intracommunity transactions between tax entities from the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="69">Thirty-one cases of commercial transactions where there were doubts as to their implementation or suspicion of VAT evasion were examined together with the Customs legislation.</seg>
<seg id="70">It was found that:</seg>
<seg id="71">In some cases, the tax authorities used information obtained through international cooperation and charged the taxpayer with VAT.</seg>
<seg id="72">In these cases, the payers either wrongly claimed the VAT exemption or did not grant the acquisition of the goods in the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="73">In some cases, the tax authorities could not use the information obtained because the information was either incomplete or incomprehensible.</seg>
<seg id="74">In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal provisions in both Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">In some cases, the tax administration of another Member State refused to reply to a request for information.</seg>
<seg id="76">There were cases where payers erroneously reported business transactions in aggregate reports.</seg>
<seg id="77">As a result, the data in VIES were incorrect and tax administrations had to examine these cases (see. 6.).</seg>
