<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in excise control between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted joint report informs on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel inspections carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Czech Audit Office of the Republic aimed at the administration of excise duties in the period following the entry of both countries into the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was carried out on the basis of a contract for cooperation in control activities concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The theme of parallel controls was selected in view of the fundamental change in the system of excise duty collection which took place in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union from 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the internal market of the European Union requires the free movement of goods, including excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow the circulation of non-taxed goods until the date of delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with that principle, the new legislation adopted in both countries allows for the movement of goods under tax supervision under suspension.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on tax administrations and envisages close synergies between Member States' competent administrations in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in excise controls for the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Control number: (Czech Republic) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject: (Czech Republic) Administration of Excise Duties (SR) Procedure of Columns</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (SAO-CR) and the Czech Audit Office of the Republic (SAO SR) concluded the "Surveillance Cooperation Agreement" on 8 February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in parallel inspections of the "Excise Tax Administration," included in the SAO-Czech Audit Plan for 2005 under No. 05/34, and "Control of the Columns Procedure for Collective Taxes," included in the SAO SR Control Plan for 2006 under No. 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">Parallel checks were coordinated.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted of exchanging information that could not be obtained by the Contracting Parties when controlling the administration of excise duties in the territory of their State and of producing a joint final report on the outcome of the checks within the meaning of the European Implementing Directives for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards - Directive No 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">In the Czech Republic, the control (hereinafter referred to as "the Czech Republic") was carried out by groups controlling from the state budget department and from the territorial unions of central Bohemia, southern Bohemia, western Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia between 7 February and 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">27 controllers were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="20">The audited persons were the Directorate-General of Customs (hereinafter referred to as the "GRC") and 11 financial offices.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the GŘC 12 selected customs offices were checked out of a total of 54.</seg>
<seg id="22">The inspection in the Slovak Republic (hereinafter "SR") was carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO SR in cooperation with exposures of the SAO SR Banská Bystrica and Košice at 5 customs offices out of a total of 9 in the period from 13 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">8 controllers were involved in the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel checks was to examine customs procedures for the administration of excise duties and compliance with relevant legislation in both countries and in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">International cooperation was focused on the practice of tax administrators in supervising the transport of excise goods, in particular on the registration of initiated and terminated transactions under suspension of tax, and on the exchange of information within the framework of mutual administrative assistance between excise administrators of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="27">The administration of excise duties in the Czech Republic was carried out by the financial authorities until 31 December 2003.</seg>
<seg id="28">As of 1 January 2004, this agenda had been taken over by the customs authorities, which had so far only levied excise duty on imports.</seg>
<seg id="29">Mineral oils, alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products are subject to excise duty in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="30">The income of the state budget from excise duties in the Czech Republic totalled CZK 82.8 billion in 2004 and excise taxes accounted for 19.5% of the state budget revenue from taxes and charges amounting to CZK 424.7 billion.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, the income of the state budget from excise duties amounted to CZK 103.6 billion and the share of the state budget revenue from taxes and charges amounting to CZK 460.4 billion was 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the income from excise duty on mineral oils to the State budget amounted to 80% of the total revenue from this tax and in 2005 it amounted to 90.9%.</seg>
<seg id="33">The difference to 100% of CZK 13 billion in 2004 and CZK 6.9 billion in 2005 was the income of the State Fund for Transport Infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of all excise duties in the SR shall be carried out by the customs authorities from 1 May 2004, with the exception of excise duty on mineral oil, the administration of which they have been administering since 1 January 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">In the meantime, tax authorities administered excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="36">Excise duty in SR is subject to mineral oil, alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="37">The state budget revenue from excise duties in Slovakia totalled SK 43.4 billion in 2004 and excise taxes accounted for 209.5 billion in total tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005, the revenue of the state budget from excise duties was Sk 50 billion and the total tax revenue of Sk 222,6 billion was Sk 22,5%.</seg>
<seg id="39">Chart 1 - Comparison of Czech state budget revenues from taxes and taxes and tax revenues of SR state budget with excise revenue</seg>
<seg id="40">The legislation in both countries relies on European Union rules governing this area, in particular: - Council Directive 92/12/EHS on the general arrangements, possession, movement and monitoring of excise products ("Directive 92/12/EEC"), - Council Regulation (EC) No 2073/2004 on administrative cooperation in the field of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as "Regulation No 2073/2004"), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 2719/92 on the accompanying official document for the transport of excise products under suspension of excise duty ("Regulation No 2719/92"), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 3649/92 on a simplified accompanying document for the movement within the Community of excise products released for domestic consumption in the Member State of dispatch ("Regulation No 3649/92").</seg>
<seg id="41">The basic legislation regulating excise duties in the Czech Republic is Act No. 353/2003 Coll., on excise taxes, as amended, (hereinafter "Act No. 353/2003 Coll.") effective from 1 January 2004.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the administration of excise duties in SR, the customs authorities are, inter alia, bound by the following generally binding legislation: - Act No 98/2004 Z. z. on the minimum tax applicable to mineraloleja as last amended (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 98/2004 of the European Parliament and of the Council"). z. "), - Law No 104/2004 Z. z. on the maximum tax on wine as last amended (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 104/2004 Z. z. "), - Law No 105/2004 Z. z. on the definitive tax on lieh as amended (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 105/2004 Z. z. "), - Law No 106/2004 Z. z. on the abovementioned tobacco tax as amended (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 106/2004 Z. z. "), - Act No 107/2004 Z. z. on the first-rate tax on beer as last amended (hereinafter referred to as "Law No 107/2004 Z. z. ").</seg>
<seg id="43">2.1 Movement of excise goods under suspension between Member States of the European Union</seg>
<seg id="44">The conditions for the movement of excise goods under suspension are governed by Directive 92/12/EHS in Title III - Movement of goods Art. 15 to 20.</seg>
<seg id="45">According to those provisions, transport of such goods may be carried out only by an authorised warehousekeeper, which means a natural or legal person authorised by the competent authorities of a Member State to produce, process, store, receive and dispatch excise products.</seg>
<seg id="46">The beneficiary in another Member State may be an authorised warehousekeeper or economic operator without the status of authorised warehousekeeper, but who may not store or dispatch such products under suspension.</seg>
<seg id="47">The authorised warehousekeeper is a tax warehouse operator in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic; the economic operator is an authorised beneficiary for repeated or one-off receipt of excise products.</seg>
<seg id="48">Under the Directive, the movement of excise products under suspension is only possible with an accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="49">The accompanying document shall be drawn up by the consignor in four copies before the start of transport unless the competent authorities of the Member State of dispatch require further copies.</seg>
<seg id="50">2.2 Procedure for the initiation and termination of transport of goods under suspension between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="51">Transport from the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="52">The procedure for the start of transport is governed by Section 25 (1). 3 of Act No. 353/2003 Coll., including:</seg>
<seg id="53">"The tax warehouse operator shall inform the local customs office responsible for the tax warehouse from which the transport is to commence prior to the start of transport of the selected products;</seg>
<seg id="54">transport of the selected products may only commence with the agreement of this customs office.</seg>
<seg id="55">The customs office shall give its consent to the transport of the selected products without delay after the condition for securing the tax is fulfilled... "</seg>
<seg id="56">The consignor in the Czech Republic may start the transport of all types of excise products only with the consent of the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="57">The customs office shall give its consent to the commencement of transport only if security is provided for the amount of the tax attributable to the products transported.</seg>
<seg id="58">The consignor is obliged to draw up the accompanying document in five copies before the start of transport.</seg>
<seg id="59">The customs office shall indicate on the accompanying document the consent to the start of transport.</seg>
<seg id="60">Copy 1 shall be retained by the consignor, copy 2, 3, and 4 by the consignor to the carrier and copy 5 shall be retained by the office authorising the transport.</seg>
<seg id="61">According to Slovak legislation, the beneficiary in the SR retains copy No 2 of the accompanying document. Copies No 3 and 4 shall confirm the receipt of the products and shall submit both copies to the competent customs office locally.</seg>
<seg id="62">Copy No 3 certified by the customs office shall be sent to the consignor not later than the 15th day of the month following the calendar month in which it accepted the products.</seg>
<seg id="63">Copy 4 shall be retained by the consignee's customs office.</seg>
<seg id="64">Transport is terminated by receipt of products by the recipient.</seg>
<seg id="65">The customs office in the Czech Republic which authorised the start of the transport will decide on the release of the security within 5 working days after the presentation of copy No. 3 of the accompanying document, which is confirmed by the consignee and the Slovak customs office.</seg>
<seg id="66">Chart No. 2 - Movement document for transport started in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="67">Transport from SR</seg>
<seg id="68">Until 31 December 2005, the procedure for the transport of alcohol and tobacco products from the SR to another Member State of the European Union was adapted as follows:</seg>
<seg id="69">According to the provisions of section 26 para. 4 of Law No 105/2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="70">"From the tax warehouse to the tax warehouse to the beneficiary of the tax warehouse, the sender" (the supplier ") shall be obliged to send an electronic fax machine to the competent authority in order to send a copy of the relevant document electronically to Colní split Poprad; it is compulsory to send to the columnist within three days from the date of the commencement. "</seg>
<seg id="71">According to the provisions of Section 22 para. 4 of Law No 106/2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="72">"In the case of tobacco products from the tax warehouse to the tax warehouse to the beneficiary, in another case the sender" (supplier ") shall be obliged to send electronically the faxom to the Czech Republic. it shall be obligatory to send to the customs authority within three days from the date of the commencement. "</seg>
<seg id="73">In the case of the transport of other excise products (mineral oil, wine and beer) between 1 May 2004 and 31 December 2005 ("the audited period"), the tax entity was not obliged to notify the Poprad Customs Office or the competent Customs Office of the start of transport under suspension.</seg>
