<seg id="191">6. Summary</seg>
<seg id="192">The cooperation between the SAO-Czech Republic and the SAO SR allowed to compare the basic legislation governing excise duties in both countries, the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the initiation and termination of the transport of products under suspension between the two countries, the registration of such transactions and further to compare the exchange of information between customs authorities in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="193">6.1 By comparing the legislation on excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, differences were found:</seg>
<seg id="194">a) in the procedure of tax entities and tax administrations when starting the transport of products under suspension.</seg>
<seg id="195">Transport of products under suspension of tax may be initiated by the tax entity in the Czech Republic only with the approval of the tax administrator, which authorizes the start of transport on condition that the products transported have been provided with a guarantee of the amount of tax attributable to them.</seg>
<seg id="196">The start of the transport of products under suspension in SR is not subject to the authorisation of the tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="197">During the audited period, the taxpayer was obliged to notify the tax administrator of the start of transport of alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="198">He could start shipping mineral oils, beer and wine without informing the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="199">In 2006, the Slovak Republic gradually adopted amendments to all excise laws under which the consignor of goods under suspension of tax is obliged to send a copy of copy No 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office which is locally responsible for the consignor before the start of transport;</seg>
<seg id="200">(b) within the time limits for dispatch of copy No 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="201">The recipient in the Czech Republic is obliged to send copy No. 3 and 4 of the accompanying document to the tax administrator for verification at the latest the following working day after the end of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="202">Certified copy No 3 shall be sent to the consignor no later than the following business day after receipt from the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="203">The consignee in the SR is obliged to send to the consignor of the products copy No 3 certified by the tax administrator and the recipient of the products no later than the 15th day of the month following the month in which he received the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">Customs authorities in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic keep electronic records of products under suspension.</seg>
<seg id="205">The content and method of keeping this record is not regulated by legislation in the Czech Republic or Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="206">The customs authorities in both countries shall enter in the register all data from the accompanying documents on the basis of which transport is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="207">There is currently no single electronic system for monitoring the transport of goods under suspension between Member States of the European Union, enabling excise administrators in each Member State to obtain real-time information on the transport of goods.</seg>
<seg id="208">According to Decision of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003, the introduction of an electronic system for monitoring the transport of excise products is foreseen from 1 July 2009.</seg>
<seg id="209">On the basis of a contract for cooperation in control activities, the Czech Party has forwarded to the Slovak party a database of products subject to suspension started in the Slovak Republic and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="210">The database contained 5,876 items relating to transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="211">The Slovak party handed over to the Czech party a database of products under suspension of tax started in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="212">The database contained 3,319 items relating to transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="213">The Czech party compared the data on the transport listed in the register started in the Czech Republic with the records of the Czech Republic terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="214">The Slovak party compared data on the transport of goods under the suspension procedure initiated in the Slovak Republic and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="215">The comparison of data was made more difficult by the fact that the quantities of goods transported were not reported uniformly in the databases.</seg>
<seg id="216">In cases where it was not possible to unambiguously assign data on each transport in both registers, a check of the accompanying documents was carried out and no breach of the suspension scheme or cases of tax evasion was detected.</seg>
<seg id="217">On the basis of the knowledge from the parallel controls, it can be concluded that Member States can obtain valuable information from the registers in order to improve the management of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="218">The establishment of an electronic system for the transport and control of excise goods within the meaning of Decision No 1152/2003/ES of the European Parliament and of the Council will allow the electronic transmission of the accompanying document and more effective control of movements under suspension of tax in the territory of the European Union.</seg>
