<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of value added tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of follow-up</seg>
<seg id="3">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxation is generally a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It therefore goes without saying that Supreme Audit Institutions (SAI) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">Examples are value added tax fraud ("VAT").</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, a loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated annually in the European Union (the "EU").</seg>
<seg id="8">Already in 2005, participants in the VI. the EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">Within this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very appropriate area for control cooperation as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic ("SAO") and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, "BRH") carried out the first parallel VAT control action in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The relevant report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not limited to a single country but is widespread across the EU, close cooperation between the SAIs is needed to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps taken to address this problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both SAIs therefore decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out a parallel follow-up check.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Control number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject: (CZ) Administration of value added tax (D) Bilateral audit with the SAO (follow-up)</seg>
<seg id="18">Control objective:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the audit action was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the administration of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure for dealing with selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter "Germany"), and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries in the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit action was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">The intention was also to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting control findings were intended to compare with the established best practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period was 2006 to 2008, in the case of factual contexts as well as the period preceding and following, until the end of the check.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions</seg>
<seg id="25">The subsequent inspection of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">During previous parallel checks, suspicious cases of intracommunity transactions were detected.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them requested further clearance.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the audit findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations on the administration of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up exercise was used to evaluate the measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspected cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also focused on selected cases of high-risk intracommunity transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of receivables and the implementation of VAT controls on large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">When reviewing VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, auditors obtained the following control findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from the previous check</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Conditions for the registration of payers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel checks, the comparison of VAT registration systems in both countries revealed differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As different marketing authorisations cause problems, both SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions for registering payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation has been presented at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The proposal for an amendment to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 ("Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003") called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including a VAT tax identification number database.</seg>
<seg id="38">It also amended common standards for registration and deregistration of tax payers.</seg>
<seg id="39">The SAI expected EU Member States to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of this document, agreed by the EU Member States under ECOFIN, no longer contains this issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to regard this intention as a relevant prevention tool to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly summary reporting</seg>
