<seg id="482">4.4.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="483">In the area of international recovery assistance, all EU Member States are subject to the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="484">Therefore, the method of processing applications for international assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic and Germany is identical.</seg>
<seg id="485">The SAO and the BRH made a comparison of the statistics submitted by the two Member States for the period 2006-2008 to the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="486">The data contained in these statistics did not match.</seg>
<seg id="487">In its 2006 report, the European Commission recommended that Member States pay increased attention to the management of their statistics.</seg>
<seg id="488">In its 2009 report, the Commission concluded that the incidence of mismatches in statistics had decreased, even though the number of applications had increased.</seg>
<seg id="489">Both SAIs consider it important to renegotiate statistics at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="490">This discussion should focus on how to avoid persistent mismatches, otherwise the data reported by individual EU countries in the statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="491">In addition, the two SAIs agree that reliable statistics should show the annual number of applications as well as the nature of the claims in question (i.e. whether the claims relate to VAT, income tax, etc.) as well as the amount of the claims recovered by each Member State.</seg>
<seg id="492">Both SAIs consider it important for the Commission to provide more detailed analyses of the statistics submitted by the Member States, as this can assist Member States in assessing their own effectiveness in combating VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="493">The fact that recovery rates can be calculated broken down by Member State, both SAIs consider it useful for Member States with lower recovery rates to step up their efforts and try to improve the recovery rate at least to the level of the EU average.</seg>
<seg id="494">If a Member State so wishes, the Commission should actively participate in this process.</seg>
<seg id="495">In particular, in 2006 and 2007, the Czech Ministry of Finance did not submit claims for recovery on time to local tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="496">A similar situation was found for applications for international assistance received from Czech tax authorities.</seg>
