<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">Differences in the responses of the two Member States show that the Czech Republic provides a system that collects the amount of data from the tax checks carried out and data from the financial statements - balance sheets and profit and loss statements.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to guide the selection of risk-inclined cases.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the analysis and management of VAT control in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, the Czech Republic is planning to establish a specialized tax office for the administration of VDS.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">This makes it more difficult to carry out those tasks in a similar way.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, Germany's philosophy places greater emphasis on the choice of individual cases on the basis of the data from the tax returns submitted.</seg>
<seg id="612">The risk management components will therefore be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of adequate reference notes, expert auditors must be able to measure the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">The two SAIs agree that Member States should be able to provide adequate financial management as well as an adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help reduce shortfalls in VAT revenues.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the yield on VAT collection will increase and the level of risk detection for unreliable entrepreneurs will improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">Cooperation between the two SAIs on parallel controls of VAT administration met the objectives set by the SAO and BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">Both SAIs have got to know each other better in the following areas: • intracommunity transactions, • VAT risk management, in particular as regards the selection of risk-inclined transactions, • assistance in the recovery of VAT claims and • VAT control of large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to mutual cooperation, differences in VAT fraud strategies and differences in the above mentioned areas of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany were revealed.</seg>
<seg id="621">The control findings have been compared and best practice identified.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAIs hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to launch a debate on approaches and strategies within Member States, including at European Commission level.</seg>
<seg id="623">The extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation of the two SAIs can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future VAT management control actions.</seg>
